<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 92 / Iraqi assets to be seized by UN
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL LITTLEJOHNS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Nations security council last night directed states that hold
blocked Iraqi oil assets to seize them to pay for food and medicines for
needy Iraqis, begin compensating victims of the invasion of Kuwait and meet
some UN peacekeeping costs.
The resolution, adopted by 14 to 0 with China abstaining, sets a limit of
Dollars 200m (Pounds 112m) per state holding funds. The money must be
transferred 'as soon as possible' to an escrow account administered by Mr
Boutros Boutros Ghali, the UN secretary general.
Officials estimated combined proceeds at a minimum of Dollars 1bn. The US
holds the bulk of the Dollars 4bn in Iraqi assets which were frozen after
the invasion of Kuwait in August 1990.
Iraq may still avert the punitive measure by ending its refusal to export up
to Dollars 1.6bn worth of oil every six months to pay for essential imports
and compensation claims. That provision was approved last year in the first
relaxation of sanctions.
In the general assembly this week, the Iraqis again objected that the terms
insulted their national sovereignty. In a bid to head off last night's
resolution, they asked instead to be allowed to sell Dollars 4bn worth of
oil, mainly for relief. They also offered to donate 5 per cent for non-Iraqi
aid, including some to Bosnia-Hercegovina.
Much of the cash raised by the seizure of assets is intended for more than
3m Kurds facing famine in northern Iraq.
</TEXT>
