<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 92 / Fears grow over coal job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID LASCELLES, Resources Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR MICHAEL HESELTINE, trade and industry secretary, met Mr John Major, the
prime minister, yesterday amid growing government worries over the economic
effect of massive job cuts in the coal industry.
The forthcoming privatisation of British Coal will be accompanied by about
30,000 job losses and pressure is mounting from local MPs to cushion the
impact of what is likely to be the most severe employment cut yet in a
state-owned concern.
Mr Tim Eggar, the energy minister who will handle the privatisation, was
also at the meeting.
The shrinkage of British Coal to a commercially viable size will devastate
areas of north-east England where there are virtually no other sources of
employment.
However, the government's determination to curb public spending in the wake
of sterling's devaluation appears to have shut off the alternatives of
postponing the privatisation or subsidising pits to keep them in operation.
There is a possibility of small amounts of EC money to help coal
communities.
The government still plans to introduce a British Coal privatisation bill,
probably by November, to keep to the timetable of auctioning British Coal
next year.
It also intends to press ahead regardless of whether new coal-based
electricity contracts are agreed in the coming weeks.
</TEXT>
