<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 92 / Big drop in house prices blamed on Pounds crisis
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HOUSE prices staged their biggest monthly fall for almost a year in
September, according to Nationwide, Britain's biggest building society.
It blamed the sterling crisis and the ending of stamp duty concessions in
August for the decline.
Average prices fell by 1.4 per cent in September compared with the previous
month, Nationwide said. The previous biggest monthly fall was 2.4 per cent
last October.
It was the fourth month in succession that prices had fallen, the society
said. The rate of decline, however, had reduced over the summer and prices
appeared to be stabilising.
According to Nationwide, on average house prices have fallen by more than 6
per cent in the past 12 months. In parts of southern England prices have
fallen by more than 30 per cent since 1988-89.
Mr John Wriglesworth, housing market analyst for UBS Phillips &amp; Drew, said
that even taking into account special factors, last month's fall was deeply
disappointing. 'Every time prices decline people stay out of the market
believing that prices may fall further. The more they stay out, the more
likely it is that prices will fall,' he said.
Mr John Hutchinson, Nationwide's corporate strategy director, said the
turmoil in currency and interest rate markets meant that September was not a
good guide to longer term price trends.
The ending of the stamp duty holiday on August 19 for houses costing less
than Pounds 250,000 meant that many people had brought purchases forward,
'leaving a vacuum in September'.
The response of potential housebuyers has been mixed in the two weeks since
Britain announced sterling's suspension within the ERM, say estate agents.
Mr David Goodchild, associate director of Aitchisons estate agents in south
Hertfordshire, said: 'In Watford and Berkhamstead there has been a sharp
increase in people wanting to view properties. In Hemel Hempstead and St
Albans, close to Hatfield where British Aerospace has just announced 3,000
redundancies, the market remains as depressed as ever.'
