<HEADLINE>
FT  03 OCT 92 / Sterling hits new D-Mark low: Major reopens row over
realignment - Bundesbank dashes hope of rate cut
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WALLER and PETER MARSH AND PHILIP STEPHENS
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SCHWERIN, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
STERLING hit a new low yesterday against the D-Mark, as Germany's Bundesbank
dashed hopes that it might lower interest rates.
The pound's weakness continued as Mr John Major, the prime minister,
reopened the war of words with the German authorities by denying that they
had requested a realignment of sterling within the European exchange rate
mechanism on the weekend before Black Wednesday.
The Treasury believes a note from the Bundesbank president, Mr Helmut
Schlesinger, published earlier this week, implied the bank sought
realignment of several currencies that weekend, September 11-12.
Mr Major, replying to a demand from Mr John Smith, the Labour leader, for an
explanation of events surrounding sterling's suspension in the ERM, wrote:
'Apart from Italy, I do not know whether the German authorities contacted
any countries that weekend and pressed them to realign.
'What I do know - and what the chancellor of the exchequer has made clear -
is that the German authorities made no request to the United Kingdom that
sterling should realign.'
The prime minister's reply did not cover the possibility that the Bundesbank
had requested a realignment before that weekend.
Mr Major also pointed out that 'all the intervention that the Bundesbank has
undertaken must be financed by the Bank of England'.
Earlier, Mr Michael Heseltine, the trade and industry secretary, had warned
that the government could not use sterling's suspension from the ERM to
allow the currency to go into free fall.
Mr Heseltine also echoed a warning earlier this week from Mr Major that the
government could not rule out tax increases next year if spending and the
deficit are not held in check.
The Treasury said the Bank of England's reserves fell by an underlying
Pounds 4.4bn last month as a result of heavy intervention by the UK
authorities in the vain effort to prop up sterling ahead of suspension from
the ERM.
The sharp fall in sterling gave an awkward jolt to Mr Norman Lamont's
preparations for what promises to be a critical Tory party conference for
the chancellor in Brighton next week.
Investors switched funds out of pounds and into D-Marks after Mr Schlesinger
said that the Bundesbank would keep its main credit rates steady for the
'time being'.
Mr Schlesinger said German credit rates were not unduly high given the
pressures of unification. Speaking after a meeting of the central bank's
council in Schwerin, eastern Germany, he revealed that total Bundesbank
intervention since the beginning of September to support weak ERM currencies
had totalled DM92bn (Pounds 36.8bn).
The Bundesbank's lack of action on interest rates was the main factor behind
the pound shedding 4 1/2 pfennigs yesterday to a close in London of DM2.43,
an 11 1/2 pfennig loss on the week. At last night's level, sterling is more
than 50 pfennigs below its former central ERM rate of DM2.95.
Pressure on sterling was exacerbated by continuing uncertainties about how
the UK intends to operate economic policy after the debacle of ERM
suspension.
The prospect of higher borrowing costs next year would raise further doubts
over Mr Lamont's future as chancellor. He already faces an uphill task in
persuading party activists next Thursday, when he is due to deliver his
conference speech, that the government still has a coherent economic
strategy.
As concern about the economy spilled over to equities, the FT-SE 100 index
of leading UK shares slipped 22.6 for a close of 2,549.7. The fall in prices
on the London market was helped by a decline on Wall Street, where the Dow
Jones Industrial Averageclosed down 53.76 at 3,200.61.
Elsewhere in Europe the effect of the lack of movement on German interest
rates added to pressures on some of the weak ERM currencies, particularly
the Portuguese escudo and the Irish punt.
The Bank of Spain was forced to increase its daily intervention borrowing
rate from 13 per cent to 14 per cent as the peseta fell to a close of 71.32
against the D-Mark, very near its ERM floor of 72.62.
The Bundesbank's council's decision to maintain its main credit rates
disappointed many investors who had been looking for an easing in monetary
policy to help the overall European economy.
The Bundesbank last reduced its rates, after being under intense
international pressure, on September 14.
