<DOCNO>FT924-15636</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAGRFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (41): Keeping in
touch with decision-makers - Facilities management supplier; User view
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID TEBBUTT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AST Transact likes to keep tabs on the key decision-makers and influential
people in some of Britain's largest financial institutions, writes David
Tebbutt. The company, majority-owned by the Royal Bank of Canada, is a
supplier of facilities management and high value software products. It uses
Market-Base to manage both mailshots and the sales process.
The company is taking a phased approach to implementation, starting with the
facilities management prospect and customer details.
The system currently contains 400 to 500 records; in total, the system is
expected to reach 1,500 researched prospects. One of the early tasks is to
mail a copy of AST's own City FM magazine to senior personnel of companies
which use IBM mainframe computers. All recipients will be addressed by name
and have a personalised letter included.
Before Market-Base, the company used ButtonWare's PC-File. This was
restricted to three contacts per company. The company also tried using
TeleMagic with one product.
Richard Wright, an AST business development manager, looked at a number of
sales and marketing systems before settling on Market-Base. He describes it
as, 'user-friendly, easy to learn and easy to use.'
He also admits that Kensington Marketing Services, its publisher, 'did an
extremely good job of selling the product. They were straight, and they
answered the questions of the whole department.'
He liked the fact that the database was hierarchical and could handle
multiple company contacts. He also liked the program's sales forecasting and
analysis capabilities, both numerical and textual. The standard reports are
not suitable but, using the Clarion report writer, Mr Wright is able to
tailor-make reports to the company's needs.
Kensington Marketing Systems helped with installing the system on a network
and on a portable PC. The supplier also converted the data files from PC
File and TeleMagic. At the moment, any three out of the 12 network users can
use Market-Base at the same time.
The system cost AST Transact Pounds 2,500 for the three-user network version
and a single-user copy for a portable computer. Mr Wright's advice to
would-be buyers of sales and marketing systems is, 'if you have no
experience of databases, use a consultant. Otherwise, the more you look at,
the more confused you'll become.'
He also suggests: 'Have a clear idea of what you want - some programs will
do too much, others will do too little.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
