<DOCNO>FT924-15637</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAGPFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (38): Wish you were
here - Holiday club streamlines its mailshots
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WHO, these days, takes their time off in a holiday camp? Information
technology staff of Holiday Club Pontins have started work on a system that
will answer that question in exact detail, writes Claire Gooding.
The survey's findings will rely not on popular mythology, but on the exact
science offered by GB mailing, a postcode-based marketing database.
Holiday Club Pontins - part of the Pounds 80m Scottish and Newcastle Leisure
Division - runs clubs at 22 locations around the southern and north-western
coast of the UK, plus outposts in Cork and Jersey. In the high season, its
team of 400 staff can swell to more than 4,000.
What is constant - according to marketing manager Pamela Knight - is the
clientele: 'We do a great deal of long-term and repeat business. Our
business is people; making sure they enjoy themselves is inherent in our
company policy. Better service to our customers is a priority.'
Part of this better service includes communicating with customers more
effectively, in Ms Knight's words, 'making sure they get the information
they require, at the time they require it, but not in duplicate.'
A problem was that Pontins data contained and duplications and discrepancies
that made it impossible to determine exactly who was who. Duplications were
inevitable because of slightly differing occurrences of the same name at one
address, sourced from holidays taken at different locations and times.
Pontins sought a packaged solution that would work on the IBM AS400 computer
 -which its information technology staff have used since 1987  - and found
only one: GB Mailing. This product has enabled Pontins to make sense of its
data with its technique of assigning a unique identification system, based
on postcodes. GB Postcoder allocates the postcode to addresses, making sure
that the mail qualifies for bulk postal discounts. The Addressplus facility
even generates all the address details, bar house-number and addressee's
name.
Each system update, every six months or so, costs Pounds 1,000: the original
price, at implementation in November 1991, was Pounds 11,495.
Pontins uses the system only on its own data, drawn from past and current
guests. The main benefits havebeen the improved accuracy of mailshots to the
750,000 names on the database, with the spin-off of telemarketing. Bookings
over the phone are now much faster and easier for both Pontins and the
customers.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVIII
</PAGE>
