<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (28): Computing
with a conscience - Claire Gooding finds out how a marketing database system
makes fund-raising more cost-effective Case Study; The Children's Society
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE SUFFERING of children has always wrung tender hearts, and won pennies
from pockets. But in a recession, the Children's Society has to work harder
than usual to fund its work among children of all races and religions, and
to keep down its administrative costs.
The marketing database system recently put in place by the information
technology (IT) staff at the Society's Marjory Street headquarters in
central London is designed to make fund-raising cost-effective.
'We had three problems to solve,' explains direct mail manager Roger
Beschizza. 'First, we needed to make our IT cost-effective.
'Secondly, we wanted to maintain and improve our marketing ability.
'Thirdly, we wanted to integrate the various incompatible systems into one.'
Like most charities, the Children's Society relies heavily on donations,
(see the society snapshot, facing page). Its administration and
fund-raising, however, is sharply divided from its 'core business' of
helping disadvantaged children - runaways, refugees, and other troubled or
abandoned children.
Even the whereabouts of its two London 'safe homes' for runaways, (to which
the police turn a benevolent blind eye), are unknown to the staff at its
central London headquarters.
Although changing social structures have made many orphanages redundant,
there are currently 146 projects, including residential centres for those
with disabilities, centres for children coming out of care, family centres,
and refuges for drug abusers.
The prefix, 'Church of England' has been downgraded in the charity's title,
because, as press officer Liz Spenser explains: 'We're for everybody. We
deal with Muslim and Somali refugees - any families or children who come to
our door.'
However, members of the Anglican Church still provide the greater part of
funds and supporters. Donations derive from cash collection boxes, and
carefully targeted fundraising campaigns, such as the Jester fun events in
April, and the recent Great Cake Bake. At headquarters, the emphasis is on
fund-raising and channelling funds. Last February, the search started for a
system that would bring all operations in-house, converting from the service
then based at the Axciom bureau.
'It was a typical bureau situation,' explains Mr Beschizza. 'There was a
geographical distance and a technical distance between what we needed and
what the bureau was able to provide.'
THE Society was looking for a much faster response time, versatility, and
better quality of data. After looking at 20 possible solutions, three were
left on the shortlist. The decisions on the new technology were made by an
IT steering group which drew staff from different divisions, with the help
of an independent consultant, Iain Pritchard, who was absorbed into the
Children's Society full-time for a year.
The process translated Roger Beschizza's 'wish list' into technical
requirements, including such elements as the computer's response time. Mr
Pritchard's final recommendation was to run two packaged software products
from CMG Business Systems on an IBM RS/ 6000 minicomputer under the Unix
operating system. The marketing database product, Infobase, links to
Fact2000 integrated accounts, and CMG's tailoring included a bridge to the
existing PC-based local area networks, running standard PC tool for
wordprocessing, spreadsheets, electronic mail and desktop publishing.
There was a massive conversion effort to sort out the existing data. The
original bureau lists contained 500,000 names and addresses, comprising
supporter and contact database, spontaneous donors, regular commitments,
appeals committees, projects and companies.
Although the job of preserving data integrity never ends, the system has
taken around a year to settle down. It took twice as long to implement as
the six months Mr Beschizza expected. Now, according to David McKee, the
operations manager, they ready to start the next phase of making the data
more useful corporately.
The conversion of the IBM mainframe formatted information from Axciom's
bureau (which the Society still uses for some purposes) was surprisingly
smooth, although the results still had to be combed, qualified and tested -
'it doesn't matter how perfect the conversion technique, there will always
be glitches in the data,' comments Mr McKee.
'The conversion program itself was 7,000 lines of code, so some
imperfections were inevitable. It wasn't until we had all the data in-house
and started working on it that we could see for ourselves exactly what was
there. Before, we were working in the dark.'
The Infobase database and the Facts 2000 accounting system are linked to
other administrative functions, such as word processing, so that donations
can be posted through accounts, with a note made on the contacts database,
and the name and address transferred automatically to Wordperfect for the
creation of 'thank you' letters and acknowlegements. There are several
different lists, such as the 'box lists' for the holders of collection
boxes, and others for area organisers, or active fund-raisers.
It is by painstaking attention to detail that the Children's Society has
built up its lists. There are of course some problems computers simply
cannot solve; poring over indecipherable signatures takes time. A reference
book of 'recognised' scrawls helps with the mystery giro slips which come in
on a regular basis from area organisers. Often the only source of
information accompanying a donation is a barely legible handwritten address
or signature, from the hand of an elderly, perhaps visually-impaired donor.
These letters are more difficult, as the supervisor of central processing,
Sheila Gay, explains: 'A Pounds 10 donation in someone's memory has to be
acknowledged, just as much as the larger amounts from fund-raising events.
That person might be a regular donor, or become one - or even consider
putting a bequest in his or her will.'
Ms Gray and her colleagues go to considerable lengths to establish correct
name and address information, particularly for donations over Pounds 100.
They also search indefatigably for postcodes, in a quest that will qualify
the direct mailshots for a Mailsort discount.
All such information now goes onto the database, which records the
activities, donations and original point of contact for each person on it.
Six months down the line, the data problems are less fundamental, more
cosmetic, and Mr McKee is more concerned with de-duplication, more with the
ability to do 'soundex' of fuzzy-match searches. It is not possible to
discover and keep details, such as age, which might allow accurate profiling
of the database, but even so, initial efforts to analyse the data have
yielded valuable information.
For instance, in a recent analysis, Roger Beschizza was surprised to find
how many of the collection boxholders were also economically active
credit-card holders. A profile of 'the typical donor' will be easier to
establish now the data is reliable - 'we came out of darkness, and into the
light - to use a Biblical phrase . . . we're now in a much better position
to use data in a way that's useful to us, rather than the way the bureau
could have provided it.'
The big benefit for the Children's Society is that it now has one database,
accessible by everybody and working more or less in real time, instead of
the out-of-date microfiches that were once their mainstay.
'That's a big plus. The spin-offs are that people support one another
because they are all working on the same system, with the same data,' he
says.
Mr Beschizza is now preparing to increase the level of science he uses in
targeting his various support groups, using his new database in management
decision-making - 'if I have a word of advice, it is: 'Get the people at the
top to own the system, make sure that everyone uses and owns it; get people
involved early in the consultation process.' '
This process, he suggests, makes staff feel more valued and reassured,
especially if they are facing technology for the first time. Going live was
traumatic for those unused to interactive computing, although, in the event,
disaster-free. He describes it as an 'arm round the shoulder operation,
requiring lots of comfort and reassurance.'
'It takes careful management of people's expectations. And it's very easy to
forget where you came from, and all the hurdles you've already conquered.
Now, we are all talking the same language, and we all understand one
anothers' systems.'
The Children's Society's contemporary attitude to raising funds is evident
in its use of IT for cost-effective operations. Nor does it miss a chance to
add to its 'soft' asset, the database.
By the end of the visit, there were two more economically-active adults on
the list as collection-box holders. For an organisation which admits it
still has some way to go in sophisticated marketing, supplying 'freebies'
that actually woo money from the recipients' pockets is no mean feat.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XV
</PAGE>
