The decision, opposed by Mr Leonid Kravchuk, the president, is being hailed
by opposition leaders as an opportunity to begin economic reforms in
Ukraine.
Parliament's vote by an overwhelming 295 to six came as a postscript to
Wednesday's resignation of Mr Vitold Fokin, the Ukrainian prime minister. Mr
Kravchuk tried to limit the damage by urging parliament to accept Mr Fokin's
resignation but leave his like-minded cabinet in place.
However, parliamentarians defied their president and voted to oust the
entire cabinet. They gave Mr Kravchuk 10 days to select a new prime
minister, and another 10 days to form a new cabinet before presenting it to
parliament for ratification.
