<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (43): New ways to
reduce errors - Claire Gooding examines the problem of questionable data
lists Sources of Information
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
A COMMON complaint among all the companies interviewed on the subject of
database marketing was that there was too much data, rather than not enough.
Worse, the quality of the data bought in from list brokers is often
questionable.
Dick Booth, managing director of Coggon Computer South is used to giving
advice to the companies who buy in data to run with his Salesnet system.
'We have done checks on imported data, using telesales techniques, and I
would say that about 30 per cent of the target data proves to be
inaccurate,' he says.
Before asking whose fault this might be, it is worth reflecting on the ways
that list brokers and market researchers come by their data.
Sometimes - as with NOP - they simply ask, and people are only too happy to
tell. But often, data derives from forms which people fill in for other
purposes, such as applying for a mortgage, a controlled circulation
magazine, or entering a trade exhibition.
All too often, the varieties of spelling, abbreviation, and titles, in the
name alone, result in multiple records and duplicates.
The stories here are about companies whose main product is data - either the
collection of it, or the refinement and delivery of it, using computer
techniques. It is now possible to buy data on CD-ROM, but a lot of work has
to be done on analys is and presentation.
Ironically, the area which most needs addressing is that of data capture,
still limited by the vagaries of handwriting, and the inevitable errors in
transcribing or punching information.
Here, computer aided interviewing, CATI, may eliminate the most error-prone
part of the loop.
One market research company, Ronin, has developed an even more sophis
ticated tool, ESBIS, the Expert Based System Interviewing Software, which
was recently used in an international survey of IT managers.
The system follows the logic by expanding on certain areas with more
detailed questions if the respondent showed interest. Most people have
become wary of filling in detailed forms: they realise now they might be
inviting unwanted mail offers.
But even if you try to remain anonymous, or, like Ronin's IT managers, feel
'over-surveyed,' then the profiling systems will still find you. You can't
hide from the postman, but you don't have to open the mail.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XIX
</PAGE>
</DOC>
