<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (44): Hunting for
prime prospects - Customer Profiles
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
COMPUTERISED databases have been the mainstay of Dunn Humby, a marketing
consultancy whose services include strategic and tactical market planning.
Its founders left the CACI consultancy to apply the same techniques to the
commercial sector as CACI has used successfully in the consumer market.
'Mosaic and Acorn are clever, but not enough to analyse businesses,'
comments Edwina Dunn, director of Dunn Humby. The company provides a service
identifying people and companies as prime prospects on a one-off basis. It
does so by creating a customer profile from data provided by the client, and
matching it to wider data sources.
Dunn Humby looked at a number of resources, including BT connections, and
Telephone Data Services, TDS - 'the larger databases tended to have a
limited number of details about a great number of companies. We wanted to
know a lot about a little - we wanted a rich, accurate data-source, so that
we could segment by employees, turnover, size or any other factor.'
Dunn Humby chose Lotus One Source's Private+ product for its depth of
detail, but also uses TDS and selected specialised databases such as
Keystroke Knowledge, for government data.
Dunn Humby takes the data supplied by the customer (usually these are
limited to address, contact details and order history), loads it into the
Oracle system, and matches company records with those within Lotus UK
Private+. The customer data is then combined with additional data from One
Source, such as detailed business description, financial and locational
details.
From this cocktail of data, it builds up a sophisticated profile of existing
customers, which is then used against the Private+ listings to identify
potential customers - 'to sell on different levels, you really need
details,' concludes Ms Dunn. 'The clever thing about the One Source data is
that it lays out the relationships - parent, subsidiary. That is unusual,
but an essential part of what we call 'relationship marketing.' '
</TEXT>
