<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (30): A better way
to raise funds - How an animal charity targets its mailings more closely
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE RSPCA, Britain's famous animal charity, has been working to protect
animals since 1824. Today, direct mailing is its lifeline: its activities
are funded entirely through donations from the public, which last year
reached Pounds 30m, a remarkable Pounds 10m increase on the previous year,
writes Claire Gooding.
The aim of its marketing database project is to increasing revenue by
producing focused mailings. Like any charity, the RSPCA is concerned with
getting good value for money. Its new marketing database is dedicated to
producing market statistics and tailored membership lists, so that direct
mailing becomes more efficient and cost-effective, the main aim being to
release funds for the animal welfare work.
From the RSPCA headquarters in Horsham, where its fund-raising and
membership activities are based, project manager David Stechler explains the
problems that faced him.
'We had 40 different databases, which we wanted to consolidate into one
source of information for in-house control and reduced cost.'
It was not just a matter of co-ordinating the various sources for the
450,000 names on the RSPCA lists, but also of bringing together three
separate services, the Axciom bureau, which produced the lists, the Brand
Direct direct marketing house, and Mail Marketing, which would analyse and
deliver response information back to Axciom.
Costs were considerable, as the RSPCA was mailing at least one campaign
monthly, and a major mailing every three months, and paying each time for
the use of the Axciom data. Mr Stechler sent his 'wish list' of features to
26 suppliers of packaged solutions.
These whittled down to a shortlist of six who were able to offer systems for
charities: CMG, the Specialist Computer Group, Donorbase, Minerva,
Systemteam and Care Business Solutions. The plan was to integrate all the
older systems for payroll, library and membership, currently on different
DEC and Data General hardware.
This scheme eliminated the PC-only solutions for the marketing database. The
RSPCA users felt most comfortable with the proposal from Care, essentially a
bespoke system based on the Empress relational database.
'We liked the people, they were local, close, and the users felt that this
product would be theirs rather than anyone else's because it could be
tailored to our requirements so closely. We felt this might give us an edge,
and we wanted an advantage over the competition.'
Now all the core systems, donation, accounts, contacts and membership, are
in one integrated system.
'We've rationalised on one HP 9000 with a PC network for all our
applications,' explains Mr Stechler. 'Our objective was to create a system
where any authorised user could access any application from any terminal.'
The RSPCA refused to reveal how much the entire project cost, but is
convinced of its benefits.
'This system is cheaper to run, and it is more effective at getting
donations because we can identify the hierarchy: people who are just
interested, those who have given members, active members. If we know who all
our contacts are, it's easier to convert a one-off contact into an active
member.'
The RSPCA's own data includes details of donations, legacies, covenants and
legacies, responses to mailshots and information from mail order trading
operations. In addition, it buys in 'cold lists' from third parties such as
list broker Dudley Jenkins.
The Care system links with GB Mailing which draws on Royal Mail address
files for postcodes, and is then linked with the Mosaic system for s
ocio-demographic analysis of postcoded addresses.
The next step, now that the system is in place, is to sample the database,
an exercise which will allow the RSPCA to target its mailings more closely,
and achieve its aim of bringing in more funds, spending less on information
technology - and more on rescuing animals in distress.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XVI
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-15671</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAG3FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
