<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (49): Flexibility
is crucial - Few software packages perfectly match the requirements. True
adaptability can be provided by supplying tools that the purchasers can use
 -The right software tools for the job
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN GRUMBALL
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A BAD workman blames his tools, so the saying goes
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
but many software packages never make the tools available in the first
place. Most professional software designers build their systems from simple
re-useable components. This enables them to change the package quickly if
market conditions dictate. However, few if any of these tools are ever made
available to the purchaser. This allows the developer to retain control of
the software.
For example, a large number of specialist packages are built around
databases. The personnel management systems discussed elsewhere in this
issue all have a database package at the core. Often this is a standard
database, such as Oracle. Surprisingly few of the vendors highlight the
advantages that this brings the system purchaser. A modern database package
allows very complex, specific reports and analyses to be produced in
minutes.
The system at the Children's Society, (see case study: page 15) has
'soundex' searches in the Oracle layer. This means that a search for the
name 'Thompson' will also match 'Thomson,' 'Thomason' and so on. It can go
further and find 'Thomas' and even 'Timson,' for example. However, the
system vendor has not brought this facility out to the surface and the
soundex searches are not available to the users. Happily, this can be
corrected by the systems staff adding a custom Oracle module themselves.
It is this sort of flexibility that can make a big difference to how a
company uses a software product. A large number of packages become
'shelfware' (ie they are bought - but never leave - the buyer's shelf)
because they cannot perform a particular function.
Although the rest of the package may be acceptable, this one lack may
condemn it. For the vendor, it has the implications of little repeat
business, even if they have sold the first copy.
Increasingly, vendors are realising the importance of customisation and
specials but the economics of software development make it prohibitively
expensive. It is not viable to spend three days (at, say, Pounds 500 per
day) customising a Pounds 100 package. However, it is possible for the user
to tackle this instead, if the correct tools are provided.
It is the users who understand their daily operations. They are the ones
with experience. They alone understand the particular inter-relationships of
their data. It differs for every company according to the culture and
traditions of the management.
While one managing director manages for cash, another looks for growth and
yet another values market share. No one standard report can encapsulate the
needs of all.
There a number of common features between each: all will need totals and
averages at some point. They will also need a set of date calculations for
things like estimating current age from date of birth or length of service
from date of joining.
What the vendors have to do is to provide these basic tools in much the same
way as calculator manufacturers provided buttons for the four common
arithmetic operations.
Increasingly, computer software vendors are using metaphors to try and
de-mystify operations. Modern spreadsheets such as Excel mimic the
traditional accountant's sheet and then add tools like 'summing' a column of
figures on a single button.
The entire GUI movement has been based on emulating a desktop on a screen.
Thus, programs overlap on the screen and whatever you are working on floats
to the top. Unfortunately, this metaphor has gone too far and many people's
screens are as jumbled as their desks.
Increasingly, non-computer people are becoming transformed subtly into
complex programmers. City dealers build complex financial models for
arbitrage calculations, little realising that they are programming.
The downside is that they do not apply the disciplines that are beaten into
the professional programmer - structure, layout and testing. Thus, many
systems are impenetrable to an outsider. Many companies attest to the
problems when the one person who developed it all leaves.
This is balanced by the use of computers as an enabling technology. Queries
and studies can be made that could never have been tackled before. KLM, the
Dutch Airline, uses a complex rostering system which saves hundreds of
thousands of pounds, (see case study: pages 8-9). It could never have been
considered with a manual system. Its sickness recording system has also
allowed them to decrease sick days and to highlight areas where healthcare
training (such as techniques in lifting to reduce back injuries) was needed.
If more data is made readily available, managers can answer more complex
strategic questions. Indeed, the next problem will be selecting the relevant
information from 'info-glut.'
Tools are an important part of software packages to enable managers to
perform their jobs more effectively. Used properly, they can cut, shape and
polish information to produce a beautiful conclusion.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XXIV
