FT  02 OCT 92 / ERM: The Anglo-German Row: City leaders bemoan the lack of a
clear government policy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BUSINESS and financial leaders in the UK warned yesterday that the absence
of a coherent economic policy and Britain's potential isolation from Europe
could damage the country's prospects for economic growth.
They urged the government to rid the country of uncertainty by adopting a
clear economic strategy. Some said that it would take a new chancellor to
implement it.
Lord Alexander, chairman of National Westminster Bank, called for a clear
commitment to Maastricht.
Mr David Lyon, chief executive of Bowater, the packaging and printing group,
which has extensive European activities, said it was essential for the
government to re-establish order in its management of exchange rate policy.
'In the absence of that we have huge movements of cash swinging around the
world not driven by trade but by people speculating in money. That
volatility is hugely damaging,' he said.
Mr Geoffrey Shingles, the UK head of Digital Equipment, the largest US
minicomputer manufacturer, said
of the UK government: 'They have got themselves in a ridiculous situation.
They had the chance to rebalance the economy and they threw it away.'
Mr Ken Schofield, chief executive of chemicals group MTM, said: 'The new row
between the German and British authorities is the final nail in Mr Lamont's
coffin. We need a new face who can make some difficult decisions.'
Mr Keith Skeoch, chief economist at James Capel, also thought Mr Lamont had
to go 'if the government is to come up with a clear-cut statement on
economic policy'.
Fear was expressed, too, that foreign companies could become nervous about
investing in a country whose position and influence in Europe was
questionable.
