<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-15695</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAF6FT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (33): Building on a
customer-base boosts profits - Northern Rock Building Society; User View
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT a time of recession in the housing market, the aim of building society
Northern Rock is to stay independent. Its marketing database is so strategic
to this aim that Jeg Gray, direct marketing manager, attributes improved
profits to the sharpening up of marketing techniques, writes Claire Gooding.
Not only has it enabled Northern Rock to avoid takeovers and mergers by
staying profitable, but it won the accolade from consultants Philips and
Drew of being 'the most improved building society in 1990.'
As the 11th biggest in Britain, with over a million customers and 1,600
employees, Northern Rock's 124 branches stretch form Inverness to Brighton,
but its main home base is in the north-east. Even here it does not pretend
to be dominant: it vies with the Halifax (17 times larger), each taking a
third of the northern market. This presented Northern Rock with a marketing
dilemma.
'We have to ensure that we are marketing led, with a range of products and
services in line with what customers and potential customers want, and from
which we can make a profit,' explains Jeg Gray.
Additional loans to existing mortgage customers is typical of the 'add-on'
services Northern Rock wanted to sell. But three or four years ago, the
company was well aware that its direct marketing was weak. It had no idea of
the 'lifetime value' of customers.
Senior executives were in on the discussions which led up to the acquisition
of some sort of marketing database, and were unanimous that in-house
resources were better used concentrating on the core business.
'Our own IT staff were busy developing new products such as mortgage and
savings plans, and managing existing systems. We decided to see what the
market had to offer in the way of designing and building a marketing
database,' he says.
Here, the financial soundness, security, and experience were the criteria.
However, in the final decision, Northern Rock chose the solution they now
run from CCN marketing not on the basis of any previous experience with
building societies, but on the willingness of CCN to tailor the service to
its precise needs, and commit considerable resources to the project. Mr Gray
has high praise for the other company on the shortlist, Printronic - 'a good
all-round solution, but CCN Systems' northern location was what finally
swung us.'
As with any marketing database, the main effort was to winnow meaningful
information from the diverse in-house accounting systems.
'It was a matter of re-structuring how we held the data, looking at people,
not accounts. We started with our own internal files, which held nuggets of
information in lots of different places.'
The data is enhanced by using CCN's Mosaic demographic database.
'This divides housing stock into 58 different categories according to
postcode,' explains Jeg Gray. 'Each postcode is relevant to around 17
houses. Mosaic also has census information available to it, so by knowing
the postcode we can find out a lot about our customers and how they conform
to profile.'
Northern Rock was one of CCN's first customers to use its Oasis data
dictionary, a proprietary product for the IBM mainframe which makes the
software adaptable to different account structures, making it possible to
look at account level, person level, or household level.
The software project took four months to complete, using a small team of
business and technical experts in the marketing database field. Now, as well
as selling additional loan products, Northern Rock is able to convince
customers of the benefits of extra security such as insurance. It
cross-sells policies to a wide range of customers, and can demonstrate that
on the savings and investment side, there are several products which have
sold solely through approaches made through the post.
CCN's service includes a monthly production cycle of enhancements and
developments, and although Northern Rock's recent purchase of a Tandem
computer with Oracle database might provide the basis of in-house support,
there are no imminent plans to make the move. On the contrary, Mr Gray
argues forcefully in favour of the bureau approach to marketing database.
'The need for database marketing, or relationship marketing, has never been
more apparent,' he says. 'The best database and strategies are likely to be
provided by people with experience. It is not necessarily an internal IT
function.'
He stresses the value of direct marketing agencies which understand the
power, flexibilities and what he calls 'strategic opportunities' that a
database can provide.
For this, he used WWAV North. Handing over such systems to outsiders is, he
says, no problem, because marketing databases can usually run alongside
accountancy-base systems.
Convincing 'the powers that be' to spend on such assistance and consultancy
could be more of a problem: the organisation has to persuade senior managers
who are used to spending millions of pounds on TV advertising that this is
good value.
Mr Gray is willing to sing the praises of the system, but wary of revealing
too much to the competition because of the edge he believes it has given
Northern Rock in the marketplace.
In the worst housing recession since the Second World War, Northern Rock's
performance outstripped others: profits were up 30 per cent, total assets up
29 per cent, and mortgage lending increased by 45 per cent - thanks to the
effort put into database marketing and direct mail three years ago, he says.
'We are able to reduce marketing costs by communicating with those customers
we consider to be more likely to be interested in the product. This is much
more cost-effective than mailing to the whole file: it's selective
marketing, the difference between junk mail and direct mail.'
So anxious is Mr Gray to promote this desirable difference that he has
become more involved in direct marketing and has taken a place on the
newly-formed board of the Direct Marketing Association.
</TEXT>
