<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (35): Bank enhances
service to clients - Account relationships are easily reviewed / Bespoke
Financial Application
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE United Bank of Kuwait undertook its database marketing project 'to
enhance relationship-banking.' A British-based consortium employing 275
people, the bank is split into two parts, dealing with investments, and a
Gulf customer-base, 95 per cent of which is Kuwaiti, writes Claire Gooding.
According to marketing officer Michelle Lamb, there was a need for improved
internal marketing information with a view to improving the service to
clients.
'When you're speaking to somebody, it is necessary to know the entire
relationship with that person, which might involve different requirements in
such areas as foreign exchange, fund management, and other departments,' she
says. The previous database, running the Focus fourth generation language
and database, simply could not cope with the organic growth of information.
The bank carried out a full study of mainframe and PC based products,
looking at internal and external resources.
It quickly decided on a bespoke application, and a series of careful
specifications and functional reviews narrowed the field. The information
had to be accessible to computer novices, so ease of use was one criterion.
With 200 private clients and 350 institutional clients, each of which would
relate to an enormous amount of detailed information, speed was another
consideration.
The bank chose the Superbase 4 language for its flexibility, ease-of-use,
and particularly the Windows-based interface. Once it had chosen the
software vehicle, it invited bids from three consultancies, Swift, Database
Management Services, and Softa.
Although its price was not the lowest, Softa won on cost and time-scales,
and worked to implement a Pounds 30,000 system on a DEC Vax minicomputer,
supporting 35 workstations. The system, called Info, includes all details of
contacts, connections and relationships, along with funds, products bought,
competitor activity and other account information. All of these financial
details are drawn upon for mailshots.
Because the project was bespoke, in-house staff wrote their own manual, but
all found the system very easy to use.
Michelle Lamb's advice is that the important element is getting the data
right - and that needs involvement from all levels: 'It's hopeless unless
you've got full support and it's being driven by senior management. In the
end, no-one will use it, not even the enthusiasts, if the data is not right.
The impetus has to come from the top: 'ownership' is vital, and especially
input from the marketing department.'
Confidence in the data, and its reliable, up-to-date integrity, are among
the system's benefits to Ms Lamb - 'now we're able to see the complete
account relationship, the next stage is to use it pro-actively.'
</TEXT>
