<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAFXFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (21): Disciplined
but flexible approach pays off - The installation of an integrated personnel
and payroll system at Hotpoint, the domestic appliance supplier, is enabling
the company to give line managers control over their own staff information /
User View; Payroll and personnel functions at Hotpoint
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MIKE KEALEY, personnel manager at Hotpoint, the domestic appliance supplier,
has firm views on how to introduce human resources computer systems
successfully .
'Keep it simple, by concentrating on getting the basic information right
first,' he says. 'Bear in mind that it's a long process to build up all the
data you want in the system. You can give line managers ownership of
information on their staff, but personnel must keep control of data input.'
These simple tenets have stood Hotpoint in good stead as it has moved to an
integrated personnel and payroll package covering 6,500 employees at three
factories, a design department, a service operation and an administrative
headquarters split between Peterborough and North Wales.
Hotpoint used to run separate payroll and personnel packages on an IBM
mainframe computer. The company then moved to DEC Vax computers and started
looking for a new system. In particular, it wanted a single, integrated
system with one common database. This would avoid duplication and ensure
that the payroll and personnel functions were always working from the same
data.
'One of my hobby-horses is that you can duplicate information on computer
systems if you're not careful,' says Mike Kealey. 'You end up with different
systems holding the same data.'
He adds: 'Payroll data is the most accurate data you have. If someone
working for you is not recorded on the system, you'll soon know about is as
soon as his first pay day comes.
'With an integrated system personnel it is using the same data, which means
for example that line managers and financial people doing budgeting are
working from accurate information.'
Hotpoint chose the Sequel package from Imago - 'we started looking a year
ago and although there were lots of mainframe and personal computer packages
there was relatively little for mid-range computers,' says Mr Kealey.
'Imago was established and 100 per cent reliable, whereas some other
products were new or still under development,' he adds. Imago also offered
the right level of flexibility.
'Other suppliers offered their package and woe betide you if you wanted to
change it,' Mike Kealey says.
'For example, with one product we couldn't change a label shown against a
particular data field, although the supplier offered to do it at a price.
Our computing department has given us a lot of support, but we didn't want
to have to start relying on them to write special programs: we didn't want
to lose the ability to drive the system ourselves.
'In addition, we had developed our own screens in line with our own needs on
our previous system over a long period and we wanted the new system to
mirror these: why re-invent the wheel?
'Some suppliers provided masses of screens - but still didn't meet our
needs. They went overboard on the amount of employee information which could
be included, which meant basic information might go over several screens.
Imago offered us instead the flexibility to recreate our existing screens
and to improve on them using facilities such as pop-up windows.'
Mike Kealey stresses that the right procedures surrounding a computer system
are vital.
'People change address and get married and so on, so you have to have manual
procedures behind the system to keep the information up-to-date,' he says.
'We have set up update screens and designed a paper form which reflects the
screen layout. The form is filled in by the employee and then becomes a data
entry document. We have done a lot of internal publicity about the
availability and importance of these disciplined procedures.'
He adds: 'It's fine to have a wonderful system offering all sorts of
analyses, but you must get the basics right: you lose credibility if one of
these reports has got someone's name wrong.'
The personnel department is now starting to give line managers direct access
to information on their staff, generally using enquiry or report facilities
set up by personnel. A side benefit of this is that it is enforcing the
procedures.
'We recently gave the design director access, which meant ownership passed
to department level,' says Mike Kealey. 'This had the effect of quickly
bringing the information up to date: when the director started coming across
missing data he very quickly gathered it. Line managers want full and
accurate information.'
Even so, the personnel department has kept central responsibility for
updating records: a line manager might spot a gap but he then gets the
appropriate form completed, which goes to personnel for entry to the system.
The one area where line managers can enter data is that of training. The
factories and the design, service and headquarters operations all manage
their own training. In the past, they kept their own records on paper.
In future, the system will hold these records and the line managers are now
starting to enter information themselves directly.
'Training is decentralised and previously the records were too, but our aim
now is to centralise the records without centralising the workload,' says
Mike Kealey. 'This means we get corporate information on the amount of
training going on, while at individual level if someone moves from service
into design, for example, information about his previous training is not
lost, because it is recorded about him in the system.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-15703</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAFWFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (20): Network
matches skills to needs - User View; Regional Health Authority
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PERSONNEL and payroll are just two out of 25 systems which are interlinked
as far as possible at East Herts Health Authority.
Since becoming a NHS trust and moving its computing away from North West
Thames Regional Health Authority, East Herts has installed a network of 20
DEC Vax and Microvax computers and around 200 personal computers. It has
adopted an open systems computing strategy designed to enable any system to
work with any other and with any data, where appropriate.
This strategy led to the choice of Peterborough Software's Open Door human
resources product, designed for open systems users running the Unix
operating system, which enables software to be moved between different
computers.
East Herts had already settled on the Ingres relational database management
package for other systems and chose Peterborough Software partly because
Open Door runs with Ingres.
'The linking of systems means, for example, that we are not just running
Open Door to pay people but also using the information in other ways from
day to day,' says East Herts computing consultant, Mr Mohan Solomon. 'For
instance, data is used by the nurse rostering system to match skills to
needs. Previously this was done manually and a ward might get two senior
sisters allocated to it.'
The integration of systems also means all activities can be costed
accurately; such information can be useful when it comes to looking at
contracting out individual activities.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page XII
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-15704</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAFVFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (19): Cost-saving,
a big reason for contracting out - Payroll bureaux date back to the 1960s
yet they are still used by companies which have brought every other system
in-house. John Kavanagh finds out why / Payroll processing; Bureau Users'
Views
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PAYROLL processing has traditionally been a mainstay of the computer bureau
business and even companies which are automating their personnel departments
are still happily contracting out the payroll. Even organisations which have
had bad experiences with payroll bureaux have simply switched to another
supplier, rather than take on the task themselves.
Yet these days there are endless payroll software packages available for
personal computers, minicomputers and mainframes of all kinds. In many cases
these packages can be integrated with personnel products which companies are
installing, enabling them to run these functions from a single database. But
still they prefer to have one of their most sensitive tasks handled by an
outside agency. Cost is a key reason mentioned by bureau users.
'We looked at bringing the payroll in-house when we changed bureaux, but it
would have been more expensive because we would have needed more people,'
says Mr Greg Judge, finance director at Manchester Polytechnic, the UK's
biggest polytechnic, with 3,000 staff.
The polytechnic switched to an on-line service provided by the CMG bureau in
April after growing frustration with another supplier. The previous bureau
had made basic mistakes such as running a payroll using an earlier month's
data.
Mr Ken Dodd, computing manager at Northumbria Ambulance Service, agrees. His
organisation uses the Compower bureau.
'We have one person managing the payroll and keying in all the data and we
would certainly need more if we ran the payroll in-house,' says Mr Dodd. 'In
addition our contract with Compower was 30 per cent cheaper than the
cheapest software package we looked at. It was also 20 per cent cheaper than
the nearest bureau competitor.'
A worthwhile investment
Greg Judge at Manchester Polytechnic points out that bureaux can keep costs
down because they use the same staff to run many companies' payrolls.
'This also means they have specialist expertise,' he says. 'Unless you have
a sizeable payroll section, it's difficult to attract suitably experienced
and qualified staff.
'Good payroll managers are hard to come by: people who are fully aware of
new legislation, penalties which the Inland Revenue and statutory pensions
authorities can impose and so on. It's worthwhile paying to have this taken
care of: a bureau takes on the risks and the problems of day-to-day
operation. I've worked for organisations which have taken the payroll
in-house and have got problems.'
Passing sensitive work and data to an outside contractor brings other
benefits, according to Mr Judge - 'the payroll can be disrupted during
industrial disputes,' he says. 'The management can in effect be held to
ransom by the payroll staff.
'In addition we have an executive payroll for heads of department and above:
people who are on individual contracts and benefits packages. Politically,
it can be better to have such information handled elsewhere rather than
internally: using a bureau means only two or three people in the poly have
access to this information.'
None of the bureau users contacted by Software At Work feel that their
payroll processing is out of their control. In some cases the work is
processed at computer centres many miles away: indeed, some of the users are
vague about where their suppliers' computers are - but feel that with modern
telecommunications this is of no concern. The user companies contacted are
quite large organisations which might need to make changes at short notice.
They have therefore all chosen or switched to services which accept data
keyed in on PCs at the customer-end and transmitted over telecommunications
links to the bureau just before the payroll is run.
Lunn Poly, the UK's biggest retail travel agent, for example, switched to
CMG last November after using a service which involved completing documents
by hand, sending them to the bureau for entering to the system, receiving
printouts of the information for checking, sending these back, checking the
corrections and so on.
'We had a deadline from the bureau which was two weeks before the payroll
run,' says Lunn Poly's chief accountant, Mr Simon Barge. 'This meant we were
always doing things outside the payroll to cope with late adjustments and
people joining the company.'
Mr Barge and others say that although they cannot start the payroll
processing run themselves they are in control.
'We tell CMG when we are ready to transmit data and we can generate report
printing runs from here, although the reports are printed at CMG,' says Mr
Barge.
Greg Judge at Manchester Polytechnic comments: 'CMG has a very flexible
package and you can specify virtually any reports you want. There are almost
unlimited permutations of the ways you can record and report on
employee-costs.'
Although a bureau holds its customers' employee master files, the data can
also be held at the customer end. Lunn Poly, for example, has taken a CMG
facility which transmits part or all of a payroll master file back to the
customer and includes a local report generator.
Lunn Poly can thus make enquiries to its own local version of the master
file, running on its network of Compaq personal computers. Indeed, as Mr
Barge points out, because changes to employee data can be entered to the
local database as they happen, this file is always more up to date than the
file held by CMG, which tends to be updated with all the changes only just
before a payroll run.
Even so, a bureau payroll system is still separate from an in-house
personnel system, not just because it is being run at a different site by a
different organisation but mainly because it is normally based on different
software and a separate database. Users contacted by Software At Work
generally recognise that the level of integration of the separate human
resources systems is not as great as it could be if everything was run
in-house, but they do not see this is a big inconvenience.
For some users this is partly because updates to payroll information, such
as the addition of new staff and changes in salary, are entered to the
in-house personnel package, which passes the data to the payroll bureau when
the customer gets its monthly processing slot.
These links, however, tend to be in one direction only: this means, for
example, that pure payroll data, such as overtime earnings, which generally
do not go through the personnel system but are keyed directly to the payroll
system, might not be readily available.
Northumbria Ambulance Service, a Percom personnel system user, has separate
payroll and personnel units - 'the definition of integration depends on how
far we want to go,' says Ken Dodd.
'Personnel can ask payroll for information. It's easy to get a person's
salary - but if you want to know how much a certain person earned on a
certain day, there might be more of a problem.'
Simon Barge at Lunn Poly, which has a personnel system developed in-house on
a Hewlett-Packard minicomputer, regards the reduced integration as a benefit
 -'full integration would save re-keying of information, but this in itself
is a control,' he says. If data is being entered from payroll and from
personnel, comparisons between the two serve as a clear-cut control.'
These and other users contacted are happy with their current bureau services
and it seems that as long as the services remain reliable, even big computer
users will prefer to contract out the payroll to specialist companies rather
than take all the risks themselves. For as Greg Judge at Manchester
Polytechnic puts it: 'For any employer, there's nothing so sensitive as
payroll.'
</TEXT>
