<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (12): A boon for
local managers - New system gives instant access to the right levels of
decision-making / User view; British Waterways
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH WATERWAYS has installed a network of IBM AS/400 business
minicomputers in regional offices which previously did not even have many
electric typewriters. The move, part of a devolution of power to the five
regions, has given local managers immediate on-line access an control of
their own financial, human resources and other information.
The network has replaced a central computing set-up, based on a Unisys
mainframe running systems, which in some cases were 20 years old.
British Waterways is responsible for 2,000 miles of inland waterways and the
associated boat-licensing, moorings, waterside property development and sale
of water to industry and supply companies. It has around 2,000 employees.
The limited experience of administration people with any form of office
automation meant that user-support was going to be important in the choice
of supplier.
'Peterborough Software were very helpful and gave excellent support to
users,' comments Mr Keith Labbett, head of audit, who was in charge of
implementing the computing strategy. 'They had standard procedures and
guidance notes, which were very useful for users who had not implemented a
system before.'
British Waterways has installed Peterborough Software's Unipay and
Unipersonnel packages. These are run centrally - 'payroll in particular is a
difficult beast, with Budget changes every year. It's hard to keep up if the
system is installed in six places.'
However, the network enables the regions to be in control of their own
information. They enter data to the systems and can access information and
work on it locally.
'The old systems were inflexible and the information was not timely and
sometimes not even accurate,' Keith Labbett says. 'We now have immediate
access down to the level where decisions are made. The central human
resources unit now acts as an advisory team: the networked system means each
manager can become his own personnel manager, too.'
See also user view on page 9: how a network matches skills to needs
</TEXT>
