<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (10): KLM Royal
Dutch Airlines - Company Snapshot
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
In a difficult year for the airline industry and the onset of price wars
over the Atlantic, KLM reported a 72 per cent decline in first-quarter net
profit in mid-August, due partly to a widening of losses at NorthWest
Airlines, the US carrier in which it owns a substantial minority stake.
Other factors behind the downturn were higher interest charges and the
absence of book profits on the sale of aircraft. KLM is in the midst of a
cost-cutting programme, but productivity of its workforce improved by 14 per
cent, compared with the first quarter last year, says the company.
In the UK, KLM is based at Hatton Cross, Heathrow Airport: it has 670 staff
at 10 UK sites.
Human resources systems: Percom for personnel, recruitment, organisation
charting, training administration; Smart Systems for time recording and
rostering; SPA Plan for pensions; Saville and Holdsworth for interviewing
and psychometric testing; Lotus for spreadsheets (1-2-3) and desk-top
publishing (Freelance); Percom and Multimate for word processing; Carapay
bureau for payroll. The systems run on a Novell network linking IBM personal
computers. System cost: Pounds 100,000.
