<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAFLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (9): Award-winning
system - KLM is saving more than Pounds 500,000 a year after linking 12 PC
personnel packages / Case study; Personnel management
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LAST YEAR, KLM's UK personnel department won an award from the Institute of
Personnel Management for linking 12 personal computer software packages.
However, the Information Technology in Personnel Award was not for technical
achievement but a recognition of the way the department has used computers
to improve the whole UK company's performance.
For a one-off purchase cost of around Pounds 100,000, it has enabled the
company to cut costs by at least Pounds 500,000 a year. KLM now has packages
for everything from personnel and pensions to time-recording,
staff-rostering, training administration, job applicant interviewing and
psychometric testing. As UK personnel manager Mr David McCammon puts it: 'We
believe there's hardly anything that human resources people do that can't be
assisted by computer and there are so many specialist software companies
around offering very high-class products.'
KLM has 670 UK staff at 10 locations across the UK, although most are at the
administrative headquarters on the edge of London's Heathrow Airport or
working at the airport itself in passenger handling, baggage loading and so
on.
In the 1980s all personnel tasks were handled manually but a growing work
load brought the department to the point where it had to choose between
increasing its staff of six and moving into computing.
KLM started towards automation in 1986 by contracting the payroll processing
out to a computer bureau and buying a personnel management system from
Percom. The first bureau wanted to sell its personnel processing service too
and became unwilling to provide links with KLM's in-house Percom package, so
the airline has now switched to the Carapay bureau.
However, the biggest headache and a long-standing problem for all airlines
was staff rostering: how to make the most productive use of staff who only
had work to do when an aircraft was arriving or being prepared for a flight.
The last flight might be completed two hours before the end of a shift,
giving staff a short day, yet on other days a late flight might demand
overtime. As Mr McCammon says: 'Shortened shifts are very nice for staff,
but a disaster for productivity and ultimately threaten jobs.'
Rostering is complex: different types of aircraft, the number of passengers,
whether there are mailbags on board and so on mean the mix of staff needed
can change from one shift to the next.
KLM already had a manual clocking-in system, so it automated this using a
software package from Smart Systems and added the company's rostering
package. Links were set up from the personnel system and into the payroll
service.
'We can now organise work and people to make sure there is work to do,' Mr
McCammon says. 'It was impossible to do this with the manual system because
there are so many variables and combinations of those variables.'
The improved rostering, bringing better use of staff and a cut in overtime,
is saving KLM around Pounds 400,000 a year. In addition, there is immediate
information on a day's operating costs.
'Our financial controller can see from day to day how much overtime is being
worked, for example, and seek an immediate explanation from line managers,'
David McCammon says. 'With the manual system it could be six weeks before
such information came through. Managers can now ask and answer immediate and
relevant questions, because the information is immediately available.'
A side benefit here is that the possibility of colleagues clocking in and
out for each other has been eliminated: the system uses a personal barcode
which is printed on the pass that each person needs to get through airport
security to their workplace. They cannot get someone else to clock in for
them, because the clock-in card is now part of the security pass they need
to get to work in the first place.
The automated capturing of attendance data has brought other benefits. The
information is transmitted over a telecommunications link to Carapay to keep
the payroll records up to date. This has eliminated the errors associated
with manual systems, when figures are written on forms.
Under the old system there was a six per cent error rate. The automated data
capture and transmission has saved an estimated one man-year of work per
year. In addition the computer system's analysis facilities have helped cut
sick leave by more than a third.
KLM keeps detailed records here, grouping reasons for absence into
categories such as head, back and chest, with seven or eight sub-groups,
such as migraine and headache, in each category. This information can
pinpoint people who take an above average number of sick days but is also
used to discover potential problems created by the work: for example,
whether there is more back trouble among baggage loaders, which might
indicate that they need new training in lifting techniques.
The information has also been used to measure the effect of KLM's flu
vaccination campaign: absences caused by flu are down 30 per cent. KLM
decided three years ago to concentrate on cutting sick leave by using the
system in this way.
As part of the campaign it took on an occupational nurse and introduced
schemes such as a cash prize draw for people who had no sick leave for three
months. The results are striking: the average number of sick days has fallen
from 10.4 in 1990 to seven this year.
'Without a computer system we couldn't even begin to measure absence in this
level of detail,' says David McCammon.
On the pensions side, KLM uses a package from SPA Plan - 'we used to use
actuaries, who are very expensive,' Mr McCammon says. 'We are now saving
Pounds 8,000 a year here and we can respond more quickly to staff
enquiries.'
Other packages have been added over the years. Percom's recruitment package
enables one person to handle all recruitment administration, including
dealing with the 5,000 unsolicited job applications that KLM receives each
year. It has stored 70 standard letters in the system and can tailor these
to individual applicants.
It also stores details on every applicant so that if a vacancy arises it can
enter the required qualifications to retrieve people who might fit the bill.
This has cut advertising costs and enabled the company to fill vacancies
very quickly: within a few hours of receiving a recent request for 15
warehouse staff the personnel department had selected 150 people and written
to invite them for interviews.
A psychometric testing package and an interviewing package, both from one of
Europe's leading occupational psychology firms, Saville and Holdsworth, have
also helped with recruitment. With the interviewing package, users enter up
to 25 personal characteristics they are seeking from a list of 64 and the
system throws up suggested questions for the interview.
'This is an example of a specialist little package costing around Pounds 300
which brings huge benefits,' says David McCammon. 'It in effect uses the
experience of leading occupational psychologists. And the questions are
good, open-ended ones which bring people out. You get better interviews and
probably better recruits.
'Using the system also increases the personnel department's professional
image in the eyes of line managers.'
Percom's organisation chart system shows individuals and their jobs and who
reports to them and also details such as their age and length of service,
which KLM uses for succession planning.
The training administration package, also from Percom, holds details of
courses and enables managers to allocate people to them, send the details to
the staff, compare costs with training budgets and so on.
The Lotus Freelance product is used for desk-top publishing, producing
charts for management, training manuals and newsletters. The Lotus 1-2-3
spreadsheet package is also used, notably for modelling the impact of
changes in staff, salaries and so on: indeed, a personal computer is taken
into negotiations with unions so that proposals and counter-proposals can be
modelled immediately to see the likely impact.
Users can load data automatically into 1-2-3 from the Percom. Most of these
products are linked together through the personnel department's Novell
network of IBM personal computers; others exchange information on disc.
But despite the level of integration, there are still some significant links
missing. At present data on new recruits, pay rises and other factors
affecting the payroll is entered to the personnel system and sent to the
time recording system, which sends it to the payroll bureau. However, the
personnel package cannot accept information from the time recording or
payroll systems. This means, for example, that although the personnel system
holds a person's basic salary it does not get information on overtime.
'If we get an enquiry about total earnings, when a person applies for a
mortgage, we have to ask separately for the payroll details to get the
overtime,' says David McCammon.
Similarly, information on sick leaves has to be keyed in to the personnel
system - 'full integration would save time, and we are looking at getting
this link in the next 12 months,' Mr McCammon says. However, nothing dulls
his enthusiasm for all the systems.
'There are so many wonderful little packages you can pull off the shelf and
get working in half an hour, with great returns,' he says. 'Even a big
company could go this way. If it can split its operation into units of, say,
2,000 people, it can use these cheap PC packages.'
Mr McCammon is so keen that he spends an hour a day at his keyboard doing
mundane data entry of basic data on new recruits, salary changes and so on:
keyboard work that anyone could do.
'Hands-on experience is very important,' he says. 'I spend an hour a day on
data entry and three hours a day getting information out. Entering data
gives me a very good knowledge of the Percom system, so I can get the most
out of it when it comes to seeking information. Senior managers should get
more hands-on experience: I'm sure many personnel managers are wasting
opportunity by not knowing the full potential of their systems.
'At the same time, doing data entry keeps me up to date with what's
happening in KLM.'
The systems have enabled the personnel department to change its own
organisation and to become a more pro-active service to managers. For
example, the time-saving aspects have enabled David McCammon's secretary not
only to become a personnel assistant but also to do all the company's
training on word processing and spreadsheets. This is saving KLM the Pounds
20,000 a year it used to spend on outside training organisations.
The pensions administrator now has the time and the information to go round
the company giving talks on pensions and advising staff. And the recruitment
person is available for careers counselling. The personnel department is
working on showing managers the type of information that is available.
'Some managers make really good use of the information but others perhaps
need training in the sort of questions they can ask us,' says David
McCammon. 'They don't fully understand yet just how much information we can
give them to help them manage their departments.'
The unions, too, are catching on to the potential of this
information-handling tool - 'the unions have been very supportive and
actually use the system: as a simple example they ask us for addressed
labels when they want to ballot their members.'
The success of the UK personnel department has led KLM operations in
Belgium, France and Germany to take on the Percom system. Greece is taking
the time recording package and the US operation is looking at what the UK is
doing. David McCammon is the ideal person for them to talk to. He turns back
to the keyboard and taps keys at lightning speed to put together yet another
complex report, listing people of specified grades in a specific department
belonging to a specified union, with their individual salaries plus an
average for the group.
'I know nothing about computers, but I do know this system and that we have
at our fingertips every bit of information we need to help run this company
efficiently,' he says.
</TEXT>
