<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (7): Promise of big
benefits - Innovative companies are using integrated software systems to
help manage human resources. They are frequently enjoying a big return on
their investments / Management briefing; Personnel packages
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN KAVANAGH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PEOPLE are arguably both a company's biggest expense and its most important
resource, yet use of full human resources computer systems to help control
the expense and manage the resource is patchy. Payroll systems have been
around since the early days of commercial computing, but personnel packages
are much more recent and integrated systems - combining all human resources
functions - are only just starting to take off.
'Personnel has always been a wild and woolly area,' says Mr John Mills,
chairman and chief executive of human resources software specialist Midland
Software.
'The traditional view is that no one tells the personnel manager what to do.
Indeed, in some areas, where there have been industrial relations problems,
the personnel department might have been more or less running the company.
This function has been one of the most resistant to computer systems.'
Personnel managers interviewed by Software At Work back this view to a point
but add that personnel automation has always taken second place to key
business systems such as accounting, order processing, manufacturing control
and stock management.
Yet as this issue of Software At Work shows, companies which have introduced
human resources systems are enjoying big returns on their investments. KLM,
for example, is saving over Pounds 500,000 a year through better staff
rostering, a 33 per cent cut in sick leave and more productive use of human
resources staff, all for a one-off cost of Pounds 100,000, (see case study:
page 8).
The key to the success at KLM and virtually all the other companies
interviewed has been the emergence of personnel systems running on personal
computers and supplied by software houses specialising in this field. This
has enabled personnel departments to overcome the problem of the low
priority given to the development of their systems. The PC package has
enabled the personnel department to set up and run its own systems from day
to day.
In some cases the database is held on the company's central mainframe
computer but control still resides in the personnel department, which
manages and accesses the information through personal computers. This
development is reflected in the 1992 Computers in Personnel survey, carried
out by the Institute of Manpower Studies. It shows that only 30 per cent of
personnel systems have the central computing department as their main source
of support, even though 38 per cent are being run on the mainframe. The
survey also reflects the emergence of software packages in this area:
two-thirds of companies with personnel systems have bought in packages and
less than a quarter are using systems developed in-house. Around 75 per cent
say their systems are acceptable or good; 80 per cent have similar views on
the technical support they get. However, the emergence of personnel systems
has raised the issue of integration with other systems, notably payroll and
pensions.
A way of controlling costs
The argument here is that data from these traditionally separate areas is
used by all three, so it makes sense to integrate the systems. This then
makes it possible to get precise information on individuals, teams and
departments from day to day to help control costs, model the impact of pay
increases or company cars, look at promotion or redundancy costs and any
other information, the extent of which is restricted only by the limits of
the user's imagination.
Integration can mean taking the approach offered by Midland Software and a
few other package suppliers of installing a single system. Or it can mean
linking separate packages from a single or different suppliers, perhaps even
including a payroll system run by an external computer bureau.
John Mills at Midland Software says a survey of big organisations by his
company shows that around five per cent set up integrated systems between
1984 and 1990 and another 15 per cent in the last two years. Around 30 per
cent will go this way over the next two years and another 30 per cent in the
mid-1990s, leaving 20 per cent looking towards the end of the century before
they take this step.
Mr Colin Richards-Carpenter, associate director of the Institute of Manpower
Studies, believes that links between personnel and payroll are needed at
very least.
'Our survey shows that only a third of personnel systems are linked directly
with payroll, although 44 per cent of managers say they need this facility
in future,' he says. 'But this leaves nearly a quarter of personnel systems
users saying a link with payroll is not required. Can someone explain the
thinking behind this?'
Even so, Mr Richards-Carpenter adds: 'It is surprising how advanced some
organisations are in connecting their personnel systems to others: for
example, 10 per cent have links with pensions, 44 per cent with spreadsheets
and 31 per cent with other systems.'
The Institute of Manpower Studies survey also shows that a third of
organisations have added modules for tasks such as recruitment
administration and training management and that most others see such
additions as high priorities.
Surprisingly, Mr Richards-Carpenter says, the areas in which little is being
done are costing, budgeting and manpower planning. John Mills at Midland
Software argues that the integration issue highlights the need for top
management concern with personnel.
'The current fragmentation is due to the lack of recognition of the
importance of personnel work, both by senior management and by personnel
itself,' Mr Mills says. 'Personnel has had changing priorities over the last
20 years: we've been through the industrial relations problems of the 1970s
and early 1980s and then the emphasis switched to staff communications and
more recently to business restructuring. So it has not been clear to
personnel what they want in terms of systems.'
There has also been the political problem of departmental boundaries, with
payroll often coming under the finance department. But an integrated system,
with just one set of records, transcends departmental boundaries - 'such
issues demand that this whole area needs to be looked at by the most senior
management.'
Human resources systems are also raising issues for line managers. Personnel
managers interviewed by Software At Work say many of the line managers they
serve are bemused by the amount of highly detailed information now available
to them. Previously, personnel had problems even supplying the number of
people in a department; now it can offer lists of people who speak French
and have two-litre cars, if required.
Personnel managers say their systems have enabled their departments to
become active service organisations, examining costs and trends and taking
this information out to the line managers. But many line managers do not
know what questions they can now ask. One way to help them is to give them
direct access to the information through their own personal computers.
Some companies are introducing access gradually, for example by letting
managers book courses for their staff through the system. As KLM's personnel
manager, Mr David McCammon, puts it: 'It's better if line managers run a
company, rather than personnel. These systems provide the information to
enable them to do that, but it can take time to change people's
perceptions.'
The satisfaction with personnel systems, largely confirmed by the Institute
of Manpower Studies survey, and the rapidly increasing take-up of these
systems reflected in other surveys, suggest that this could be a big growth
area in the 1990s.
As Colin Richards-Carpenter at the Institute of Manpower Studies says: 'The
modern personnel system is a very powerful tool and organisations seem to be
having few problems justifying the investment.'
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
