<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (5): When is an
import an acquisition? - The impact of rule changes regarding the movement
of goods within the single European market is only just beginning to dawn on
many UK companies / New VAT regulations
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
ON JANUARY 1, next year, new VAT regulations come into force in the European
Community, the most far-reaching changes since VAT was introduced 19 years
ago. By 1997, a Community-wide system will be in place, but in the meantime,
the new regulations bridge the gap between the 1997 rules and the current
national VAT systems. This is one step along the road to creating a single
market of 380m consumers.
In effect, the 1993 changes abolish fiscal and physical border controls. The
complex paperwork presently required to import and export goods across
borders will be replaced with a set of regular reports and statistics.
There are three separate requirements:
EC sales listings.
Requirement to account for the acquisition of goods.
The statistical returns, known as 'intrastat,' which record the intra-EC
movement of goods.
In some cases, (businesses paying more than Pounds 2m VAT a year), returns
or at least VAT payments will have to made monthly instead of every three
months. There will be heavy penalties for those unable to supply the
information within the time limit.
Although the new regulations are designed to simplify import/export work,
they are likely to create more work in other quarters. They shift the focus
to accounting procedures, because they ask for information which has not up
to now been systematically stored.
To introduce any level of automation, most existing computerised accounting
systems will be affected: sales order-processing, purchase order-processing,
accounts receivable, accounts payable, fixed assets and inventory.
Even if freight forwarders undertake to register the information, most
companies will still have to cope with a substantial amount of manual
collection and collation of information to submit their VAT reports.
Few companies are fully prepared for the changes, which demand that all
goods bought, sold or transferred between EC countries appear on VAT returns
as acquisitions (imports) or despatches (exports).
'The VAT people think it's a problem for the systems people, and the systems
people think it all belongs to the VAT people,' comments Richard
Collier-Keywood, a tax partner in Coopers &amp; Lybrand.
His mission is to put a sense of urgency into companies who have done little
so far to prepare. He estimates that only a tenth of those affected have
begun to assess the detailed system changes, which will apply to the top 24
per cent of traders, accounting for 97 per cent of the value of all exports
and imports.
'Unless they have replaced a system in the last couple of years, the vast
majority of companies will still be working with national systems which have
grown organically as the company has grown.'
Implications are dawning
The adjustment of internal, particularly bespoke systems will cause the
biggest headaches, he suggests. Package suppliers can cater for the changes
within their own software, and some have done so, but users have to cope
with systems integration, particularly the passage and recording of data
between systems.
'People are beginning to get the message,' he concludes. 'The volume of
concerned phone calls is mounting as people realise the implications.'
Among the points he highlights from the 50 or so pages of VAT legislation
are the requirements by January 1993:
Lists of VAT registration numbers of customers.
EC sales listings for intra-EC export sales.
Systems to recognise intra-EC imports to make them subject to the reverse
VAT charge procedure and account correctly for output and input VAT.
Detailed statistical returns for both imports and exports for each
transaction.
Ability of systems to cope with several different VAT rates (from 1997).
From 1992, the new boxes 6 and 7 on the VAT return form have to be completed
by importers and exporters. From 1993, the extra requirements will be added
to the VAT100 form: VAT on goods acquired from other member states, and a
subtotal output tax. There will be a small de minimis limit which will
enable smaller companies not to submit the EC sales listing.
As not all of Europe is within the EC, existing systems will have to
distinguish between EC and non-EC countries. Freight forwarders and clearing
agents have in the past dealt with the import/export requirements (the
Single Administrative Document), so they are in a good position to help with
the new data regulations.
The customs authorities are ready to encourage the use of electronic data
interchange (EDI) techniques to ease paperwork, and systems already exist to
take advantage of this.
Computing Services for Industry, a UK-based software house, has developed
its CIEL/400 freight forwarding software to cope with the new regulations,
producing the new Intrastat data as well as the SAD.
One of Europe's largest freight forwarding operators, the Swedish-based
Bilspedition group, has already licensed the system worldwide. Even if such
systems relieve some of the administrative overhead, most companies will
have to retrain and re-deploy staff.
Inevitably the change means considering introducing new systems, or
augmenting existing ones by downloading new data. In making the changes,
users and software developers who have invested in flexible development
tools (software engineering) will begin to see the payoff. Their systems
should be more forgiving of such major additions and changes. But even the
best-prepared will have to be quick on their feet to comply. Some countries,
namely Greece and Italy, have not even produced draft legislation, and by
July, only Denmark and Ireland had ratified their laws. For details on the
Single Market, see page 6.
More Details on the Single Market
'The Single Market - the Facts,' tenth edition, August 1992; also Single
Market News, Autumn edition, (page 26); from Department of Trade and
Industry; available via DTI hotline: 081 200 1992; for enquiries via fax:
071.215 6140;
'VAT and the Single Market' - a Coopers and Lybrand report; Richard
Collier-Keywood in London, tel. 071 583 5000, ext. 23997.
'The Single Market and You': Institute of Chartered Accountants Update: tel.
071 628 7060.
Single European Market, EDCS (electronic data capture services); version 2,
July 1992, HM Customs and Excise, IT Divisions, branch 23, tel 0702 366191.
'The Management Guide to Selection and Implementation of Computer Systems,'
by Allan F Robb of KPMG Management Consulting, 8, Salisbury Square, London,
EC4Y 8BB, tel. 071 236 8000, ext 8137; NCC/Blackwell ISBN 1-85554-163-7,
(chapter 4, Europe and the trend towards pan-European accounting systems).
Succeeding through Information Technology in the Single Market: PA
Consulting Group; Pounds 12.95; from Mercury Books, tel. 081 682 3858.
'VAT for 1993' - D&amp;B Software (contact Hilary Gasper), tel 0272 276866.
'Europe: Accounting in the Single Market'; taped interview with David
Alexander, plus Coda News on Europe by Rodney Potts; both available from
Coda, tel 0423 509999.
'The European Accounting Guide,' by David Alexander, Leeds Business School,
Academic Press; Pounds 49.50; deals with accounting practices in the EC and
in leading non-member states.
'Natural Language Markets: Commercial Strategies,' Ovum July 1991; tel. 071
255 2670.
</TEXT>
