<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (6): Overcoming
time-zone problems - Pepsi-Cola International / Messaging network
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOIA SHILLINGFORD
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PEPSI-COLA INTERNATIONAL is going to base the hub of its new messaging
network in Britain, although its headquarters are in the US. Why? Because
the UK business day overlaps with part of the business day in each of the
main countries in which the company operates.
This enables Pepsi-Cola International (a subsidiary of US food and drink
company, PepsiCo) to provide users with a single source of support. It is
particularly important when the company is trying to consolidate monthly
figures from around the world, some coming from areas where
telecommunication links are poor.
The centre can advise on alternative ways of sending figures into the
messaging system (eg via telex machine).
Another factor in Pepsi's choice of location was that some telecommunication
charges in Britain were among the lowest of the countries it looked at.
The system, which goes live in October, will be managed and supported by US
computer company Digital Equipment Corporation from its UK centre at
Newbury, Berkshire.
The main hub of the network, a Vax computer in Newbury, will provide
electronic mail (e-mail) and file transfer (including spreadsheets) between
personal computers located at 60 of Pepsi's offices worldwide. The network
is based on the internationally-agreed X400 electronic mail (or 'e-mail)
standard.
Digital will run the messaging system under a five-year, fixed-price,
single-supplier agreement worth Pounds 2.5m. It will bill Pepsi companies in
dollars via electronic mail, but they will pay in local currency.
Vicki Hill, Pepsi-Cola International's US-based telecommunications manager,
says the messaging system offers higher speeds and more flexibility than the
company's current messaging system. It will also cost Pounds 3.5m less over
five years.
In addition, she expects e-mail to replace some telephone calls, especially
across time zones.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page IV
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT924-15719</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-CJBCAAFGFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>921002
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (4): Fog in
channel, Europe cut off - Business in a wider market  Whether this famous
old headline is apocryphal or not, it sums up an isolationist attitude that
has sidelined too many British companies when operating in Europe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CLAIRE GOODING
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE hot topic in this issue of Software at Work is also a hot potato. In
less than four months' time, from the start of 1993, new European value
added tax (VAT) regulations will come into force, (see next page). Few
companies are prepared for the change, which will effectively abolish import
and export paperwork for intra-EC trade, but instead bring them within the
scope of additional reporting requirements.
But accounts and paperwork are only a part of a much broader subject which
includes national regulations, language, and culture. All of these factors
have an impact on software, not only for the developers of software
packages, but for the international operators who have to integrate systems
across different national borders.
Software At Work has already touched on this topic in previous issues, when
interviewing companies such as Unilever (Spring 1992 issue). There are a few
truly global companies who have blazed trails in 'global software': they
tend to be those whose goods have to be researched, marketed, and
distributed globally, for whom economies of scale are vital.
For them, every piece of software acquired, whether developed in-house or
bought in as a package, is an investment which has to be maximised by
integration across national borders. (See Citibank report, page six). It is
difficult enough to select the 'right solution' for one country, let alone a
dozen. A constant theme of Software At Work stories is the 'ownership' of
systems and the wooing and consultation of users in their implementation.
Add national considerations and regulations, and the problem escalates. Even
if the package supplier has built in multi-currency and multi-lingual
features, there are still such problems as price negotiations and support.
Pricing can be a constant headache, with currency changes and complications
of distribution. ECsoft, a multinational supplier of software tools and
consultancy, claims to be the only supplier to have cracked this problem
with a single price list in ECUs, and a single licence agreement for all its
products.
International co-ordination
Dr Peter Maier is the managing director of Sony Europa, with headquarters in
Germany. In previous jobs he had grappled with worldwide management issues,
and for Sony he is now responsible for pan-European corporate planning and
control, as well as for information systems serving a company with 13,500
employees and a DM15bn turnover.
'Sony started to think about pan-European management as an issue about four
years ago,' he explains. 'The business concept of harmonising information
technology in Europe means that we have to look at issues both as a user and
a supplier of software.'
He uses the term 'local globalisation' to describe the process by which
standard software is adapted. The responsibility for this lies with Sony
European Computer Services, based in Dusseldorf, and made up of 100 IT staff
of different European nationalities.
Co-ordination of software purchasing rests in the Dusseldorf HQ, which
effectively becomes an assessor of various European packages. A pan-European
conference dedicated to accounting gives staff the chance to 'audit' strong
and weak features, including multi-currency, and VAT. For accounting
(usually the first multi-national system to be considered), Sony chose D&amp;B
software, formerly the McCormack and Dodge accounting package, largely
because all the groundwork on national features was already there.
Some aspects simply cannot be managed by the package route, partly because
they rely on interpreting or linking existing systems. Sony, for instance,
has built its own Executive Information System (EIS).
'Whatever we do, it must pay respect to the national culture,' comments Dr
Maier. 'We have to tailor, modify, change colour and flavour. For instance,
we standardise only as necessary: we have to know the price of something but
don't care how it appears.'
Good management means help, not control, to Dr Maier - 'the headquarters
which can't provide a professional software service will die. It is
two-thirds help, and one-third control. That ultimately enables the
organisation to develop.'
Languages
As an increasing number of companies take an international view of software
procurement, most major software developers have had to stay one step ahead,
providing different language versions as well as catering for 'national'
features.
Nearly all software developments in the last few years have taken this into
account, by separating the text that appears on screen from the actual code.
This enables vendors in each country to translate most of the essentials
(such as screen prompts and error messages), although quirks of language and
keyboards still have to be overcome.
Computer translation is becoming more practical, although companies such as
Berlitz offer a more conventional route to translation. (UK consultancy Ovum
has recently surveyed the tools available for 'natural translation' of
products, and looked at the use of different languages in pan-European
offices.)
US companies have had a 'level playing field' at home on which to promote
their products and find a user base. But in entering Europe, they have had
to translate and adapt.
Electronic mail supplier Verimation, for example, now supplies its Memo
software in 12 languages, and provides pan-European support. DEC's
All-in-One integrated office system was translated into 12 different Local
Language Versions, but since 1988 has relied on a single international code
base, from which all country or language versions derive.
Microcom, a supplier of PC remote-control utilities, unable to set up
individual offices for marketing and support, relies on local translation
and distribution services. But these can hold snags, particularly where
high-tech translators are thin on the ground: 'remote control' was once
translated as a TV flip-channel gadget rather than as a remote access
function. This highlights the need, stressed by Ovum and others, to use
native speakers for translation.
Regulations and culture
UK software suppliers can no longer be insular, particularly in the area of
accounting. They are likely to find their packages assessed alongside
offerings which originated in Germany (such as SAP) or Scala, from Sweden,
which supports 30 different currencies and supports up to 20 languages
simultaneously.
Coda, Tetra, Financial Solutions, Kewill, Edwards and Systems Union are
among the UK companies who have risen to the challenge, and an increasing
number of their installations cross national boundaries. Although it is
comforting to know that steps are being taken to promote harmonisation,
there is a limited amount of practical help available from European
'self-help groups' such as the EC's European Software and Systems
Initiative, (ESSI) or the Eureka Software Factory Forum (a group dedicated
to creating European software tools).
For the most part, developers have to explore the rules and regulations for
themselves, and be alert to every new change of regulation. This makes it
all the more essential to have a flexible base to the package, allowing
tailoring, parameterisation, and extensions.
Without this, the cost of maintenance, borne by suppliers and passed on to
users, becomes intolerable.
Suppliers of accounting packages are in the front line in Europeanisation.
Having grappled with the rules themselves to incorporate various required
features in their packages, they are in a good position to guide and educate
their user-base.
D&amp;B Software, for instance, is alerting its users to the new VAT regulations
with a folder of information which brings together all the new requirements,
including new fields and codes.
Yorkshire-based Coda sells its multi-lingual, multi-company accounting
systems, based on IBM's AS400 minicomputer, to national and multi-national
companies. Increasingly, it looks to Europe for new sales, and has tailored
its software accordingly.
'Firstly, there are cosmetic differences in the way we record even the most
basic data,' says Coda's managing director, Rodney Potts.
'Everybody knows that Belgian francs and Italian lire are recorded without
decimals.
'Lire require larger value fields, and - outside the UK - the decimal
separator is a comma. VAT is handled differently, too: for instance, Belgian
VAT reports require a special modulus 11 check built into the account
coding, while VAT accounting in Italy and Spain have substantially different
implications to other EC countries.'
But, he points out, there are also deep-seated cultural differences in
European nations, rooted in historical factors. These explain, for example,
the German emphasis on cost-accounting and the French habit of settling by
cheque.
Over the years, Coda has been building such national characteristics into
its IAS suite.
Another UK accounting house, Tetra, has essentially made a fresh start with
its new Chameleon 2000 system. Julian Blomfield, who has waded through yards
of paperwork to make Chameleon European, picks up on the cultural point made
by Mr Potts.
'You can write software to do anything if you pay enough, but it's a matter
of convincing people to make the change. No matter how much legislation
there is, you've still got to get people to work together.'
Tetra uses the Informix database as its flexible base, the aim being to
incorporate into the core all the 'customised' national functions. The
company recognises that the resellers will have an important role in guiding
users through the complexities of an all-embracing package.
'A lot of end users may be looking to their local reseller,' predicts Mr
Blomfield. 'They may well take on the role of consultants in helping users
organise the way they use the software.'
For further reading and for sources of information on VAT and the Single
Market: see panel on the next page.
</TEXT>
