<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Survey of Software at Work - Autumn 1992 (2): The
information imperative - Comment Today's technology now gives managers the
ability to choose the exact level of business information they need - but
without the right training, this crucial selection process may prove
difficult and lead to data overload
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FOR THE first time, perhaps, since the beginning of the modern computer era,
business people have the opportunity to make information their servant,
rather than their master.
The reasons for this profound shift in the business paradigm are to do with
improvements in technology: with the growth of distributed computing
systems, client-server architectures and object-orientated programming - all
topics that have been dealt with in recent issues of Software at Work.
Making the most of the opportunity will mean that, also for the first time,
executives will have to take the responsibility for choosing and defining
their information requirements.
Peter Drucker, doyen among management experts, recently told a seminar that
people at every level must develop information responsibility: 'They must
ask themselves what information they need to do their job, when, from whom
and in what form, and what information they owe to other people.
'The right answer is not 'as much as possible,' but 'as little as possible'
 -only what I need, because otherwise I cannot digest it,' Drucker argued.
Executives, however, may find it hard to decide on the information that is
most important for their job. They have become used to the systems
department dictating what information they can have and when. Staff will
have to be trained to define their information needs.
Early attempts to give senior managers information at their fingertips
failed for a variety of reasons; the inflexibility of the systems and a
reluctance among top managers to use keyboards put paid to early 'executive
information systems,' (EIS).
Robert Cringely, a US industry observer, notes in his gossipy book
Accidental Empires: 'The idea was that the Big Boss would be able to look
into the bowels of the company and know instantly how many widgets were
being produced in the Muncie plant . . . but American business executives
didn't know how to type and didn't want to learn.'
Those who did develop keyboard skills, however, were hardly able to roam at
will through the thousands of megabytes of information which constituted
their company files. Essentially, those early systems provided an electronic
slide show; a way of looking at information, carefully prepared by data
processing staff. In many companies it became a computerised version of the
'Blue Book' (or Red Book or Green Book), the collection of key business
statistics, updated monthly.
The electronic version might be updated minute by minute and it might allow
its users to 'drill down' through layers of data to investigate exceptions
and anomalies, but it remained essentially a static record, prepared in
advance. Free-ranging enquiries were simply not possible.
Professor Enid Mumford, one of the UK's leading computing academics,
outlined the problem in a recent paper: 'Developers tend to assume that all
managers have the same needs and this belief can turn EIS into information
straight-jackets, instead of providers of relevant data. The attempt to
provide 'general solutions' has failed because all companies do not have the
same business problems. Also the complexity of today's business environment
means that problems are becoming more different, rather than more similar,
even in the same industry.'
The term EIS, in any case, is looking dated. First, because it is now
appreciated that it is not only 'executives' who need access to corporate
data, but employees at every level of the organisation. Second, because
there should be no need of a special system to provide information of the
right quality.
As John Kavanagh illustrates in his articles on personnel systems in this
issue of Software at Work, substantial efficiencies and economies should
flow from any properly designed management information systems. Designing a
system properly, however, is a big challenge. Professor Mumford - best-known
for her research on the ways in which humans interact with computer systems
 -has an interest to declare because she is now commercially associated with
an innovative new management information technology, but her criticism of
the inflexibility of earlier EIS systems is well taken.
As this issue makes clear, the personnel area is one where software packages
have been designed to allow personnel people to define the information they
want. Generally, however, managers tend to identify the data they used most
recently; or they concentrate on the information used by their own
department ignoring the wider needs of the company.
Her solution involves a combination of group discussions and with a
cybernetic model derived from the work of Professor Stafford Beer designed
for the analysis of managers' roles and responsibilities.
The model provides the basis for the group discussion through which managers
agree the problems they wish to address - and the information needed to
address them. Professor Mumford's approach may not suit every company, but
it is an important step in the right direction. Instead of bombarding
everyone with everything, it is important to provide the right information
to the people who need it.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
