<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Letter: V-2 rocket pioneers guided by space-age dream
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   From Mr H. KROMER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Sir, Why are the British furious about the commemoration of the V-2 rocket?
To me, they seem to have lost the ability to take an unbiased view of that
fantastic technological breakthrough.
I am proud of the fact that inventors and engineers from my country opened
the gate to space technology and the landing on the moon. As early as the
1930s the ingenious Dr Werner von Braun dreamt of the space age and - to put
it bluntly - the V-2 was an aunt of the famous Saturn V b.
Those pioneers were guided by space enthusiasm and not by the idea of
bombing the British capital.
I think you would have to concede that Sir Arthur Harris did not have that
dream when he was bombing women and children in Dresden.
Hermann-Josef Kromer,
Im Edle 11,
7930 Ehingen 2, Germany
</TEXT>
