FT  02 OCT 92 / World Stock Markets: Kuwait falls as expected
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
KUWAIT, which reopened on Monday following a two year closure forced by the
Iraqi invasion, closed its week apparently 22.4 per cent down on a temporary
index set up by an independent company; but the fall came within pre-opening
predictions, agencies report.
Alshal Economic Consultants said yesterday that its provisional 'Alshal
Index' for the period measured the value of stocks between August 1, 1990 -
the last trading day before the August 2 Iraqi invasion - and the last
trading day of each week.
The index closed at 77.6, down 22.4. Volume during the three days was 2.89m
shares valued at 1.21m Kuwaiti dinars (Dollars 4.14m) for an average of
963,000 shares, and 403,000 dinars a day.
Initial trading was limited and local observers said that trading was
cautious because of the weakness of the economy, which had led to
preductions of a 25 per cent fall in the market before it reopened.
</TEXT>
