<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / International Company News: Digital to cut costs by Dollars
1bn a year
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LOUISE KEHOE
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SAN FRANCISCO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
MR ROBERT PALMER, who yesterday took over at the helm of Digital Equipment,
the US computer manufacturer, said yesterday he intended to cut costs by
Dollars 1bn a year to restore the struggling company to profitability.
He said he would rationalise the company's product line, eliminate
redundancy in research and development and increase the pace at which the
company was reducing the size of its workforce.
'Reducing unnecessary expense is vital and we are looking at every expense,
whether large or small.'
Digital, once second only to International Business Machines among
international computer companies, has reported losses for the past two
fiscal years. For the 1992 financial year ended in June, the company
recorded losses of Dollars 2.7bn on sales of Dollars 7.7bn while in 1991
losses were Dollars 617m on sales of Dollars 8.3bn.
'The historically high profit margin on hardware and the business model upon
which Digital was built are no longer sustainable,' Mr Palmer said.
Digital has been hit hard by moves to smaller, less expensive computer
systems which command significantly lower gross profit margins than the
company's traditional minicomputer lines. It also failed to move quickly
enough into personal computers and open or industry standard systems.
Mr Palmer was speaking on his first day as president and chief executive,
the post he has taken over from Mr Kenneth Olsen, Digital's founder, who was
principally identified with the company's failure to keep pace with the new
structure of the industry.
Mr Palmer said: 'Digital is going to change. It will take time but we are
going to begin today. Digital will undergo a transformation.'
He said Digital would refocus its research and development spending.
'Our plan will be to reduce and re-allocate funds to support research and
development that satisfies customers and provides an appropriate level of
return. This will be a cultural change for Digital.'
There was overlap and redundancy within Digital's current product line, Mr
Palmer acknowledged.
</TEXT>
