<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / US report on BCCI attacks Bank
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN FRIEDMAN, ANDREW JACK and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England was yesterday accused of 'wholly inadequate' regulation
of the Bank of Credit and Commerce International, and of withholding
information about BCCI's frauds for 15 months before closing the bank.
This was the conclusion of a four-year US Senate sub-committee investigation
into BCCI by Senator John Kerry, the Massachusetts Democrat, and Senator
Hank Brown, a Colorado Republican, in a report published yesterday in
Washington.
The Kerry report said that although the Bank received evidence of BCCI fraud
in the spring of 1990 it 'colluded in the suppression of the true facts
concerning BCCI's financial status and its involvement in fraud'.
Although the 780-page report does not offer any conclusive new evidence
about the fraud, it states that alleged errors in judgment by the Bank
'collectively materially contributed to the losses incurred' by BCCI's
depositors and creditors in the closure of the bank on July 5 1991.
Mr Kerry yesterday attacked the Bank for having 'acquiesced' in allowing Abu
Dhabi, the BCCI majority shareholder, to remove vital documents from Britain
in 1990 as a quid pro quo for Abu Dhabi's agreement to restructure BCCI. The
Bank yesterday would not comment, saying it had to maintain confidentiality
until the publication of Lord Justice Bingham's inquiry into BCCI's
supervision. The Bingham report is expected this month.
The Bank said it was not asked to supply documents or evidence to Senator
Kerry. It believed that Lord Justice Bingham's inquiry would be more
thorough as he had examined documents and interviewed Bank officials.
The Kerry report claimed Abu Dhabi's involvement in BCCI was greater than
acknowledged.
Senator Kerry disclosed yesterday that Abu Dhabi is under investigation by
Mr Robert Morgenthau, the New York district attorney who brought BCCI fraud
charges last year. Abu Dhabi last night rejected the findings contained in
the Kerry report.
The report also criticised Price Waterhouse, BCCI's auditors. It claimed
that as early as 1987, Price Waterhouse had 'ample reason' to recognise
there could be no basis for certifying BCCI's books and records gave a true
and fair view of BCCI's finances.
Senator Kerry was especially swingeing over what he termed 'a direct
conflict of interest' by Price Waterhouse partners who received loans from
BCCI while auditing the bank's operation.
Price Waterhouse rejected the Kerry report findings as full of
'unsubstantiated assertions', and expressed outrage that the committee had
not responded to its offer to talk to it in London.
More than 90 per cent of creditors to BCCI have voted for the joint
liquidators' plan, in another move to its acceptance. The vote on the plan,
involving payment to creditors of Dollars 1.2bn (Pounds 691m) to Dollars
1.7bn, was ordered by the Luxembourg court. The plan has been approved in
the UK and Cayman Island courts.
Report details, Page 9
</TEXT>
