<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Arts: Joshua Bell - Concert
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID MURRAY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Over many years in the Festival Hall, the BBC Symphony has offered
programmes for serious music-lovers - serious enough to know that they could
listen free at home, with digital sound, instead of paying something close
to the independent orchestras' prices for good seats. In the hall, audiences
were often painfully sparse. This season, all seats for the BBCSO concerts
cost Pounds 9, all unreserved - and the experience of live music-making,
after all, is beyond price. Not enough people know that yet; but on
Wednesday it was a pleasure to find eager listeners crowding the front
two-thirds of the hall, instead of being thinly spaced by income-level gaps.
If there was a specific attraction, it was hard to pin it down. Perhaps the
young virtuoso Joshua Bell, in Prokofiev's Violin Concerto no. 1 - but
virtuoso-groupies would not have warmed to Alexander Goehr's crypto-serial
Little Symphony (1963) with the generosity of this audience. (Andrew Davis
conducted it with lucid sympathy; it sounded not only serenely cogent but
full of aural imagination, plain but telling.) Nor, surely, would sober
Goehr fans have been enticed by the closing piece, Vaughan Williams'
pictorial 'A London Symphony' from 50 years earlier, though I expect Davis
did it equal justice.
What was certain was that Bell gave a marvellous account of the Prokofiev
concerto, superbly assured and fresh, even dewy - as if it carried no
daunting virtuoso-history. It does have such a history, including a
celebrated Isaac Stern recording that every concert violinist knows. Bell
might have been deliberately refusing comparisons. Instead of mimicking
Stern's strict-time raptness at the start and the close, he was teasingly
hesitant and fanciful; the 'effects' - disembodied whistling in high
harmonics, gypsy snarls sul ponticello (rough bowing near the bridge of the
instrument) - sounded like spontaneous dramatic colour. All of it lived and
breathed.
Amid a generation of alarmingly gifted violin-players, Bell and the Siberian
Maxim Vengerov (even younger) stand out by virtue of early discovery and
precocious maturity. They make a fascinating contrast, a bit like Domingo v.
Pavarotti: the one a conscious, self-effacing artist with an imagination and
a technique equal to almost anything that musical ends could require, the
other a 'natural', purpose-born phenomenon of instinctive musicianship - but
those tenors were grown-up performers when they hit their stride, and these
violinists are barely past adolescence. Should either of them be run over by
a bus, you may spend years regretting that you didn't hear them live.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
