<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / The Labour Party at Blackpool: Divisions resurface on
electoral reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BETHAN HUTTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
WIDE division at all levels of the party over whether it should back
electoral reform and proportional representation erupted at the Labour
conference yesterday.
A heated debate showed no clear consensus over the direction the party
should take. Supporters of PR, who fear Labour will continue to be denied
power under the present system, clashed with those who objected to a Labour
manifesto being diluted in a coalition government.
Delegates approved a second 'interim report' of the working party on
electoral reform chaired by Professor Raymond Plant. The working party hints
that it is moving towards recommending an additional member system for
parliamentary elections.
But Mrs Margaret Beckett, Labour's deputy leader and a member of the Plant
committee, told delegates that any alternative would be weighed against the
current 'first past the post' system - which Professor Plant himself
acknowledged may yet remain under Labour's eventual proposals.
'There is no one perfect, correct, theoretically supreme voting system,' Mrs
Beckett said.
The Plant committee reports next spring. Mr Robin Cook, a member of the
shadow cabinet and the Labour campaign for electoral reform, has called for
a commitment to change at next year's conference.
Mrs Jean Lord, of the Littleborough and Saddleworth Labour party, said she
wanted 'a Labour government.' She said: 'I don't want a coalition. We hear
that PR is fairer to smaller parties. I didn't join the Labour party to be
fair to the Liberals.'
Mr John Kemp, from Dundee West, said: 'The simple fact is that the present
electoral system . . . has for almost a century all but marginalised the
Labour party.' Deals with other parties could come up under 'first past the
post' too.
Mr Jeff Rooker, MP for Birmingham Perry Barr and chair of the electoral
reform campaign, pointed to the lack of representation for more than 1m
Labour voters in 16 shire counties that did not elect a single Labour MP,
compared with the 54 Labour MPs elected by fewer voters in the 11 largest
cities.
Two motions - one backing PR and another opposing it - were withdrawn on the
recommendation of the NEC to avoid pre-empting the conclusions of the Plant
committee.
</TEXT>
