<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Ex-chairman of Imperial: Obituary of Geoffrey Kent
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
GEOFFREY KENT, former chairman and chief executive of Imperial Group, who
led the tobacco conglomerate's unsuccessful defence against Hanson's
takeover bid in 1985-86, has died at the age of 70.
Mr Kent, who with a deceptively diffident public manner had brought a
disciplined, hands-on management style to Imperial in the four years of his
leadership, resigned from the group after the takeover.
He became chairman of Mansfield Brewery in 1989 and remained a director of
Lloyds Bank, joining its board in 1981.
Educated at Blackpool Grammar School, which he left for wartime service in
RAF Coastal Command, Mr Kent began his career in advertising. He worked for
Coleman, Prentice &amp; Varley, then one of London's leading agencies, and
Johnson &amp; Johnson before joining Imperial as marketing manager for John
Player in 1958.
Mr Kent quickly established his reputation in the competitive cigarette
market. He was responsible for the long-running slogan 'People love Players'
and created a number of popular cigarette brands. They included Player's No
6, for a time the country's best-selling cigarette, and perhaps most notably
John Player Special, with its distinctive black packet and successful motor
racing sponsorship. Mr Kent became joint managing director of John Player in
1969, and six years later chairman and managing director.
He moved to Courage, then Imperial's brewing subsidiary, in 1978 as chairman
and chief executive, and brought his marketing skills to bear on its
fortunes. His 'Cockney pub' advertising campaign helped to change the face
of beer advertising.
Three years later, after a boardroom coup, he took over leadership of
Imperial.
After the Hanson takeover, which overturned plans for a merger of Imperial
and United Biscuits, he remained unattached to any company for two years
until Mansfield invited him to become its chairman.
His marketing talents were again employed there, and he led the company out
of a series of diversified activities back to its core beer business.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
