<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / PSA arm taken over by Tarmac: Government pays buyer Pounds
50m
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW TAYLOR, Construction Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TARMAC, Britain's biggest construction and building materials group,
yesterday took over the Property Services Agency's projects division. The
move puts under threat the jobs of 900 former government employees.
The government has paid the company almost Pounds 50m to take over
responsibility for the division, one of the country's biggest construction
organisations, employing 1,800 people.
Mr John Redwood, environment minister, said: 'It was the best deal we could
have got. It would have cost the taxpayer a lot more if we had been forced
to shut down the division rather than disposing of it to Tarmac.'
For many years the projects division has designed and managed the
construction of buildings for government and other public-sector bodies.
Tarmac said it could guarantee work for only 925 people.
The Environment Department said it was too early to say how many people
would be left without work. Some might be employed on a temporary basis with
Tarmac. Others might be transferred elsewhere in the public sector or opt
for voluntary redundancy.
Mr Redwood said the cash payment to Tarmac recognised that money needed to
be invested in the business if it was to continue. In addition to the Pounds
49.75m payment, the government had offered to provide financial assistance
to help with redundancy payments if they rose above a certain level.
He said Tarmac's offer was chosen from a final shortlist of six. About 60
companies, including some international groups, originally expressed
interest in acquiring the division. attracted by the prospect of taking
advantage of its public-sector contacts. The division, which last year had a
turnover of Pounds 190m has wide experience of building offices, courts,
prisons, laboratories, civil and military airports. Its experience of
public-sector building requirements and strong links with government
departments has meant that it has continued to win a large share of work
even though most public-sector construction contracts are now subject to
competitive tender.
Control of the Property Services Agency is being switched to the private
sector in two stages, and the PSA's building management operations will be
offered for sale later this year.
NEW DESIGN orders for construction work have fallen and there is little
chance of improvement next year, the Royal Institute of British Architects
said in its quarterly report yesterday.
The value of new commissions fell 14 per cent to Pounds 1.12bn in the second
quarter of this year. Wales and Scotland were worst affected, with 36 per
cent falls in orders. The south-west was the only area to record a rise in
new commissions, up 14 per cent.
The institute said: 'The optimism generated by the election has disappeared.
Despondency is the order of the day throughout the industry. Our view is
that 1993 will be another year of depressed workloads for the profession.'
Just 18 per cent of practices expect a rise in work over the next six
months, compared with 28 per cent last quarter.
A further 126 staff are to be made redundant at the Construction Industry
Training Board, which blamed reduced income due to the recession.
</TEXT>
