<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Chancellor delays to fight another day: The public-spending
round
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE decision to delay the until Monday yesterday's planned meeting of the
public expenditure committee chaired by Mr Norman Lamont at least means that
the embattled chancellor is not having to fight on every front at once.
The hard decisions cannot be postponed for long and the signs are that
public-sector pay and capital projects will be sacrificed in order to keep
to the Pounds 244.5bn planning total.
The desperation as Whitehall and Downing Street try to find a way through
next year's expenditure is illustrated by the serious scrutiny of the
manifesto pledge on child benefit to see if taxing the benefit could be made
compatible with the words, whatever the spirit of the commitment.
Mr Michael Portillo, Treasury chief secretary, is said to have knocked a
'significant sum' off the threatened Pounds 14bn overbids for next year, but
the task this year is made more, not less, difficult by the mix of the old
and new systems.
In future years, cyclically affected spending such as unemployment benefit
will be stripped out of the 'control total' so that it does not affect
departmental programme spending in the years when it rises most quickly. For
1993-94 it is included within the planning total, however.
That allows for social security payments to rise to Pounds 76bn next year,
on the basis of a jobless total of 2.4m. The reality is likely to be 3m or
more, leading automatically to an increase in spending of at least Pounds
2bn. Against that background, public-sector pay has become an obvious
target. At a meeting with Tory backbenchers a week ago, MPs singled out pay
as a prime area for cuts.
The climate may well make the government feel it has a winnable
presentational fight on its hands if it aims for an increase of no more than
2 per cent in public-sector pay.
Relative job security in the public sector has an obvious value as
unemployment continues to rise, while the findings of the New Earnings
Survey, published last week, that public-sector pay has outstripped
private-sector pay for the first time since 1986, will also provide
ammunition.
Much of the public-sector pay bill, running at more than Pounds 70bn and
rising by about 10 per cent a year recently, is within ministers' control
it. The government can determine pay for the Civil Service and for the armed
forces, as well as for teachers and those health service workers who are
covered by pay review bodies whose recommendations ministers can decide to
stage.
The main difficulty is 2.3m local authority staff, for whom the government
can influence a settlement through the amount of grant it distributes, but
cannot control. Councils are old adversaries for the government, but the
year when the council tax is introduced is not necessarily the one ministers
would have chosen for a propaganda battle on local spending. Nonetheless,
the attractions of reducing the pay bill to help salvage some capital
projects are evident. Both ministers and backbenchers have come under
pressure from lobbies and constituents fearful that delays or cancellations
will damage the construction industry still further.
Inevitably, however, capital spending is not escaping unscathed. With the
recession reducing traffic congestion, the Pounds 2.5bn planned for road
building next year looks vulnerable, and it is hard to see the Pounds 2bn a
year for the Housing Corporation surviving intact, particularly as housing
has not managed to achieve the political status of health or education.
Equally, however persuasive the Ministry of Defence is about the immediate
costs of cancelling projects such as the European fighter Aircraft, the
Pounds 24.5bn MoD budget is regarded with greedy eyes.
Nor will the Pounds 26bn-plus for the three territorial departments
(Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland) be immune in the way it would once
have been under the formula ensuring that they automatically received due
proportions of spending in England.
There is little sign of a de minimis rule: in terms of billions, the Pounds
75m for a new prison service headquarters in Derby seems little enough, but
the project has already been cancelled just a couple of weeks after the
first brick was laid and the construction contract signed.
One Treasury official compared the new, strict public-spending regime which
the government was imposing on itself with the external economic discipline
that had been embraced in joining the European exchange rate mechanism. The
analogy is not a comfortable one for any of those involved.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 16
</PAGE>
