FT  02 OCT 92 / Many roofing sites 'unsafe'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CATHERINE MILTON, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
NEARLY a quarter of all roofing sites inspected this summer were shut down
because they broke safety law, the Health and Safety Executive said
yesterday.
In a four-month national inspection drive starting in May, 2,596 roofs were
checked and 29 prosecutions completed. One contractor was fined Pounds
20,000 - the statutory maximum - for offences involving a death.
More than 600 prohibition notices were issued, forcing contractors to stop
work until workplaces complied with safety law. The average fine was Pounds
2,500. Almost 100 more prosecutions are being considered.
Dr Tim Carter, the HSE's field operations' director, said the figures showed
that bad safety practice was 'deep-rooted' in the roofing industry. 'For too
long, roof work has been seen as a rogue industry attracting the
unscrupulous 'get-rich-quick' brigade.'
More than one in five of deaths in construction occurs during roof work.
About three workers a month are killed falling off roofs and passers-by have
been hit by falling materials. In the past three years, 109 workers have
been killed and more than 2,500 seriously injured.
The HSE estimates that there are more than 7,000 roofing contractors in
Britain employing about 30,000 workers. Almost 75 per cent of roof workers
are with companies employing three people or fewer.
The HSE says it is still analysing the 2,596 reports and plans to monitor
the impact of its campaign. It believes it has been successful in raising
contractors' awareness of safety.
Next year the HSE plans to run a similar campaign which will focus on the
use of protective equipment.
