<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Cash-strapped councils run for cover: The expected strains
from a steep rise in premiums
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD LAPPER and ANDREW ADONIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
EXETER City Council's insurance policies with the troubled Municipal Mutual
expired on Wednesday night. Yesterday, having failed to obtain cover
elsewhere, it closed its leisure facilities and took all its vehicles off
the road.
Aerobics classes and guided tours were suddenly halted as the council met in
emergency session to resolve the crisis. Mr Chester Long, council leader,
said the authority had two firms of brokers working all day and could secure
only one 'highly unsatisfactory' offer which, for some aspects of business,
was four times the MMI premium.
Exeter's troubles are an extreme example of the difficulties many councils
face as a result of the demise of Municipal Mutual, which stopped writing
new business and temporarily stopped paying claims on Wednesday.
Municipal Mutual insured the great majority of local risks. Councils face
steep increases in premiums, as well as sizeable reductions in the amount of
insurance cover they are likely to obtain after their policies expire.
Hard hit by two years of record losses and with their own capital bases
depleted, other insurance companies are not enthusiastic about selling
policies to local authorities, although their business is worth over Pounds
600m a year. Some cover is available at the Lloyd's market, but
underwriters, stung by losses, are taking a cautious approach.
Insurance brokers have been able to find alternatives but are negotiating
cover on a case-by-case basis.
One broker said yesterday: 'It is extraordinary to see the ninth-largest
insurer going insolvent and the insurance industry unable to do anything
about it.'
Insurers are worried about claims arising from awards to victims of the
'pin-down' disciplinary regime, the epidemic of arson attacks on schools,
and the cost of cleaning up contaminated land, which they fear might fall on
public liability policies.
Contraction in the insurance market means coverage on the basis offered by
MMI will be much more expensive. Jardine International yesterday offered a
one-month policy covering employers' liability, public and product liability
and most other risks, quoting prices well above the rates councils had been
used to.
Eastleigh District Council yesterday bought a Jardine policy, allowing it to
operate its bus services.
Mr Arthur Boulter, local-government director of the Chartered Institute of
Public Finance and Accountancy, said premium increases of 30 per cent to 40
per cent appear to be 'par for the course'.
Mr Boulter said: 'There is no obligation on local authorities to insure
themselves, but it would be imprudent for them not to do so. They should
also exercise extreme care to ensure that the use of cars for private use,
and the like, is properly covered.'
With spending of most councils capped by the government, and next year's
spending limits certain to be tight, the implications for council budgets
are serious. Mr Bob Block, chief executive of Oxford City Council, said he
expected to have to find an extra Pounds 100,000 for insurance cover on a
capped budget of Pounds 18m.
Spending limits from the Department of the Environment for councils make no
specific allowance for insurance. The department said it was 'very unlikely'
that the standard spending assessment targets for councils would be altered
next year to account for higher insurance costs.
The difficulties may also mean a tougher time for local-authority managers.
Mr Peter Friend, of brokers Leslie &amp; Godwin, which arranged insurance
coverage for about 40 councils over the past year, suggests managements will
come under more pressure to contain claims.
He says insurers are likely to offer less cover, insisting on much bigger
excesses. Brokers will also offer consultancy services to councils advising
them on how they can reduce the number of smaller claims.
Local-authority associations are anxious to play down crisis talk. The
associations, which yesterday met Municipal Mutual, still hope the company
will be able to meet claims on outstanding policies.
Mr Brian Briscoe, chief executive of Hertfordshire county council - almost
all of whose insurance is covered by MMI - said MMI's troubles were of
'extreme concern, but not a matter for panic'.
In the 'worst case', Hertfordshire may face a bill of up to Pounds 5m in
uncovered claims and increased premiums. But, provided MMI met past and
current claims, the cost would probably be in 'hundreds of thousands'.
A number of authorities had already begun to shift their insurance cover
away from MMI before the collapse. Newcastle and Leeds city councils for
example, have moved a significant proportion of cover to other companies and
both are paying lower premiums than those offered by MMI.
Mr James Gravenor, Newcastle-upon-Tyne's assistant treasurer, said the city
was prepared to pay 'significant excesses' in moving its remaining MMI
cover, and predicted 'a marked trend towards more self-insurance'.
Editorial Comment, Page 22
</TEXT>
