<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Howard favours 'green' taxes
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX, Environment Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
TAXES AND permits head a list of 441 new measures to improve the environment
in the government's second annual progress report on its 'green' policies.
The report, published on the second anniversary of the white paper This
Common Inheritance, lists the progress - or lack of it - on more than 440
environmental commitments.
Mr Chris Smith, Labour environment spokesman, attacked the document as
'appallingly self-congratulatory' and joined environmental groups in
criticising its failure to integrate transport and energy policies with
green issues.
Presenting the report Mr Michael Howard, environment secretary, said: 'I
have a general preference for economic instruments where they work more
effectively than regulation'.
Among possible new tools, the government is considering higher fuel prices,
road pricing, tradable permits for industrial emissions and a carbon tax.
Mr Howard acknowledged that no date had been set for the start of any of
those. Road pricing proposals would have to wait for a Department of
Transport study, to be published in a year at the earliest. The report -
which follows statements from Mr Howard on the importance of stricter
enforcement of EC regulation - spells out several important delays and
failures in government policies. They include:
A year's likely delay in publishing the review of renewable energy strategy,
due in spring 1992.
More than a year's likely delay in publishing a strategy for nuclear
research, due in late 1991.
Failure of most local authorities to publish recycling plans by August 1992.
Failure to introduce regulation on genetically modified organisms, due May
in 1992.
The 441 new proposals include:
New air quality standards to reduce ground-level ozone, benzene and carbon
monoxide to be set by 1993, and for sulphur dioxide and butadience by 1994.
New water quality standards to be introduced next year.
New standards for waste sites from 1993.
This Common Inheritance - The Second Year Report. HMSO. Pounds 21.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
