<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / Blow for housebuilding body in competition case
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT RICE, Legal Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE NATIONAL House Building Council yesterday lost its legal battle against
the findings of a 1991 Monopolies and Mergers Commission inquiry into new
housing warranty services.
A High Court judge rejected the council's application for judicial review of
the MMC's conclusion that its 10-year structural warranty scheme was
anti-competitive and against the public interest.
The council had argued that the conclusion was 'irrational' and could
fatally undermine the economics of the council and the protection it gives
to house buyers.
The case focused on a council rule requiring builders to present for
inspection every home under construction and to obtain a structural warranty
policy from the council.
Mr Peter Lilley, then trade and industry secretary, had accepted the MMC's
finding that the rule could restrict competition by deterring builders from
using alternative warranty schemes available from other insurers.
The council's main insurance competitor is Foundation 15 - a subsidiary of
the leading local government insurer Municipal Mutual Insurance, which last
night imposed an indefinite freeze on claims payments.
Mr Basil Bean, council chief executive, said after the hearing that the
organisation was considering an appeal. 'The MMC's recommendations threaten
the interests of new home buyers,' he added.
The MMC said last night it was delighted with the decision. In the past five
years there have been 10 judicial review challenges to MMC decisions
including the NHBC case. In five cases the MMC's decisions were upheld; two
are under appeal and two relating to the supply of razor blades are still
pending.
</TEXT>
