<HEADLINE>
FT  02 OCT 92 / VSEL job cuts add to Cumbria gloom
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN HAMILTON FAZEY, Northern Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A FURTHER 390 redundancies were announced yesterday by VSEL, the nuclear
submarine shipyard in Barrow-in-Furness, Cumbria. The cuts will reduce the
workforce to under 8,000 from 14,500 two years ago.
The company said yesterday that it might eventually have to slim down the
workforce to about 5,000 because of defence cuts following the end of the
Cold War and the difficulties of breaking into depressed civilian markets -
such as offshore components - in the continuing recession. It had previously
hoped to bottom out with about 2,000 more jobs.
The latest job losses will add urgency to the visit to Barrow today of Mr
Michael Heseltine, trade and industry secretary, who will launch the Pounds
1m Cumbria Marketing Initiative, aimed at improving the promotion of Cumbria
to potential inward investors.
The initiative is supported by British Nuclear Fuels, Cumbria County Council
and the Department of Trade and Industry. The chairman will be Mr John
Hancock, chief executive of Sealy, Silentnight's bed-manufacturing
subsidiary, in Aspatria.
BNF is shedding about 1,000 local jobs over the next six months, now that
construction of its thermal oxide reprocessing plant at Sellafield is over.
But while BNF and VSEL are creating structural unemployment, Cumbria is also
counting the cost of recession - more than 1,850 other jobs have either gone
since 1990 or are scheduled to by next March.
Seven companies are involved, in the textiles, footwear, bus manufacture and
computer-aided design and manufacturing sectors.
The effect will be to wipe out most of the 4,000 jobs brought in by
intensive economic development initiatives since the last big wave of
structural unemployment caused by steel and coal closures in the Workington
and Whitehaven areas during the 1980s.
The latest cuts by VSEL will take effect in January. Numbers needed for the
development stage of Britain's Trident submarine programme peaked at about
14,500 just as construction of HMS Vanguard, the first of four boats, began.
The next two submarines - Victorious and Vigilant - are in production at
18-month intervals behind Vanguard, while parts of the unnamed fourth boat
are in the pre-assembly stage. The programme will guarantee about 5,000 jobs
to the end of 1994.
By then, unemployment is predicted to rise to 15.4 per cent in the Barrow
area, to 16.5 per cent around Whitehaven and to 17.7 per cent around
Workington.
Industrial and county leaders will today press Mr Heseltine for development
area status so the area can compete with Scotland and Wales in offering
financial aid to potential inward investors.
Mr Howard Davies, director general of the Confederation of British Industry,
yesterday called for another interest rate cut and urged a 'coherent'
approach to economic policy.
</TEXT>
