FT  02 OCT 92 / Franco told to take over in Brazil today
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By CHRISTINA LAMB
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRASLIA
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THERE was such concern in Brazil yesterday over the power vacuum at the top
that the Senate insisted Vice-President Itamar Franco take over as acting
president today.
Last night, there was still no-one named to occupy the crucial new finance
ministry in the incoming administration, but Mr Francisco Gros, Central Bank
president, said he had been asked to stay on.
Mr Franco had asked for a delay in his take-over until Monday because of
difficulties in choosing, as head of the finance ministry, someone
acceptable to the wide range of parties supporting him.
The Senate decision left Mr Franco rushing to finish compiling his cabinet.
His spokesman said that he would not assume power without having named a
finance minister.
His task was helped last night when the two main parties disputing - the
Democratic Movement (PMDB) and the Social Democrats (PSDB) - agreed to stop
vetoing names. For the last two days, they had been wrangling bitterly over
the finance portfolio.
The first choice of Mr Jose Serra, an economist from the social democratic
PSDB party, was vetoed by Mr Orestes Quercia, leader of the Democratic
Movement party (PMDB). He believes that, as the largest party, the PMDB
should command the finance ministry.
Mr Franco seemed impatient with the in-fighting yesterday: 'I choose the
ministers. Anyone who thinks he can pressure me is fooling himself.'
The failure to name a finance minister and, while Mr Gros's position was
still in doubt, a Central Bank chief, was causing concern in the financial
community, anxious for word on future economic policy. The main Sao Paulo
stock market was operating 1.1 per cent down yesterday afternoon in quiet
trading, but closed up 4.8 per cent on news that the acting president would
be installed today.
The socialist Senator Jose Bisol yesterday criticised the delay: 'We are
running the risk of disappointing the nation which took to the streets in
favour of impeachment' of President Fernando Collor, newly on trial by the
senate on corruption charges.
The delay left him still in office, despite the vote by the House of
Representatives on Tuesday to strip the president of his powers and send him
to a Senate trial. He spent yesterday in his offices, where he could still
nominate appointees and issue decrees until he has signed the papers
required to suspend him from office for 180 days during the trial.
</TEXT>
